{"title_page": "Land of Confusion", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=June 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2014}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Land of Confusion\n| cover      = Genesis-Land-of-confusion-single-cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Original single cover parodying 1963's ''[[With the Beatles]]''\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Genesis (band)|Genesis]]\n| album      = [[Invisible Touch]]\n| B-side     = Feeding the Fire\n| released   = 1986\n| format     =\n* [[Phonograph record|7\"]]\n* [[Twelve-inch single|12\"]]\n* [[CD single|CD]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Pop rock]]<ref>{{cite web|first= Dodie |last= Miller-Gould |title= \"Land of Confusion\" by Disturbed one of the best covers of a Genesis song |website= LemonWire |date= 19 April 2018 |accessdate= 16 January 2019 |url= https://lemonwire.com/2018/04/19/land-of-confusion-by-disturbed-one-of-the-best-cover-songs/ |quote= The tribal drums and the keyboard or synthesizer effects way off on the treble side of the soundscape give the song a nuanced feel that shows it as more than just a heavy metal song that used to be a pop-rock song.}}</ref>\n| length     = 4:45\n| label      =\n* [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]] {{small|US}}\n* [[Virgin Records|Virgin]] {{small|UK}}\n| writer     =\n* [[Mike Rutherford]]\n* [[Tony Banks (musician)|Tony Banks]]\n* [[Phil Collins]]\n| producer   =\n* [[Genesis (band)|Genesis]]\n* [[Hugh Padgham]]\n| prev_title = [[In Too Deep (Genesis song)|In Too Deep]]\n| prev_year  = 1986\n| next_title = [[Tonight, Tonight, Tonight]]\n| next_year  = 1987\n| misc       = \n{{Audio sample\n | type       = single\n | file       = GenesisLandofConfusion.ogg\n}}\n}}\n\"'''Land of Confusion'''\" is a song by the English rock band [[Genesis (band)|Genesis]] from their 1986 album ''[[Invisible Touch]]''. The song was the third track on the album and was the third track released as a single, reaching No. 4 in the U.S.<ref name=\"awards\"/> and No. 14 in the UK in late 1986.<ref name=\"UK\"/> It also reached No. 8 in the [[Netherlands]]. The music was written by the band, while the lyrics were written by guitarist [[Mike Rutherford]].<ref>{{cite web|first= Anil |last= Prasad |title= Genesis: Turning it on again |work= Innerviews |accessdate= 27 May 2012 |url= http://www.innerviews.org/inner/genesis.html}}</ref> The song's video featured puppets from the 1980s UK sketch show ''[[Spitting Image]]''.\n\n==Music video==\n{{Original research|section|date=September 2017}}\n[[File:LandofConfusionscreenshot1.JPG|left|250px|thumb|The band members (Banks, Collins and Rutherford) as they appeared in the video.]]\nThe song is widely remembered for its music video, which had heavy airplay on [[MTV]]. The video features [[caricature]] puppets by the British television show ''[[Spitting Image]]''. After [[Phil Collins]] saw a caricatured version of himself on the show, he commissioned the show's creators, [[Peter Fluck]] and [[Roger Law]], to create puppets of the entire band, as well as all the characters in the video.\n\nThe video opens with a caricatured [[Ronald Reagan]] (voiced by [[Chris Barrie]]), [[Nancy Reagan]], and a monkey, going to bed at 4:30 PM. Nancy is absorbed in reading ''His Way'', [[Kitty Kelley]]'s unauthorized biography of [[Frank Sinatra]]. Reagan, holding a teddy bear, kisses the monkey goodnight and goes to sleep and begins to have a nightmar], which sets the premise for the entire video. The video intermittently features a line of stomping feet, illustrating an army marching through a swamp, and they pick up heads of [[Cold War]]-era political figures in the swamp along the way.\n\nCaricatured versions of the band members are shown playing instruments on stage during a concert: [[Tony Banks (musician)|Tony Banks]] on an array of synthesizers (as well as a cash register full of cookies), [[Mike Rutherford]] on a [[Multi-neck guitar|four-necked guitar]], and two Phil Collins puppets: one on the drums, and one singing.\n\nDuring the second verse, the video features various world leaders giving speeches on large video screens in front of mass crowds; the video shows [[Benito Mussolini]], [[Ruhollah Khomeini|Ayatollah Khomeini]], [[Mikhail Gorbachev]] and his aides, and [[Muammar Gaddafi]]. Meanwhile, Reagan is shown putting on a [[Superman]] suit, fumbling along the way, while Collins sings,\n\n<blockquote><poem>\nOh Superman where are you now\nWhen everything's gone wrong somehow\nThe men of steel, the men of power\nAre losing control by the hour.\n</poem></blockquote>\n\nMeanwhile, the \"real world\" Reagan is shown blowing bubbles in a puddle of his own sweat (at one point, a rubber duck floats by).\n\nDuring the bridge, the Superman-costumed Reagan and a dinosaur (with punk jewellery) watch a television showing various clips (apparently from the ''Spitting Image'' show itself), including [[Johnny Carson]], [[Walter Cronkite]], [[Richard Nixon]], [[Leonard Nimoy]] as Mr. [[Spock]] (with a [[Rubik's Cube]]), and [[Bob Hope]]. This segues into a sequence apparently set in prehistoric times, where the two dinosaurs (one wearing a bow-tie) meet up with Ron and Nancy Reagan and a rather outlandish mammal eats an egg and reads a newspaper. At the end of this part, the chimpanzee from the prologue is shown throwing a bone in the air.\n\nAs the bone begins to fall there is a sudden switch to Collins catching a falling phone which he uses to inform the person on the other end that he \"won't be coming home tonight, my generation will put it right\" (which is when a caricature of a 1980s [[Pete Townshend]] is seen playing a chord on guitar and giving a thumb-up and on the \"we're not just making promises\" verse the bone lands (on top of [[David Bowie]] and [[Bob Dylan]], but misses [[Mick Jagger]]). Reagan is then shown riding a dinosaur through the streets while wearing a cowboy hat and wardrobe. As the video nears its climax, there are periodic scenes of a large group of spoofed celebrity puppets, including [[Tina Turner]], [[Michael Jackson]], [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], [[Prince (musician)|Prince]], [[Bill Cosby]], [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth]], [[Princess Diana]] and [[Hulk Hogan]] singing along to the chorus of the song, with [[Pope John Paul II]] playing an electric guitar.\n\nAt the end of the video, Reagan awakens from his dream, and surfaces from the sweat surrounding him; Nancy at this point is wearing a [[Snorkeling|snorkel]]. After taking a drink (missing his mouth and, indeed, his face, afflicting him with \"[[Alcoholism|drinking problems]]\", [[wikt:Special:Search/a la|\u00e0 la]] ''[[Airplane!]]''), he fumbles for a button next to his bed. He intends to push the one labelled \"Nurse\", but instead presses the one titled \"[[Nuclear weapon|Nuke]]\", setting off a nuclear explosion. Reagan then replies: \"That's one heck of a nurse!\" Nancy whacks him over the head with her snorkel.\n\nThe video, directed by John Lloyd and Jim Yukich, and produced by Jon Blair, won the short-lived [[Grammy Award]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Concept Music Video#Recipients|Best Concept Music Video]] during the [[30th Annual Grammy Awards#Award winners|30th Annual Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|title= Grammy Awards \u2013 1987 |website= [[Dotdash|About.com]] |url= http://80music.about.com/library/grammy/bl_1987.htm |archivedate= 21 September 2005 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20050921002536/http://80music.about.com/library/grammy/bl_1987.htm}}</ref> The video was also nominated for an [[MTV Video Music Award for Video of the Year]] in 1987, but lost to \"[[Sledgehammer (Peter Gabriel song)|Sledgehammer]]\" by [[Peter Gabriel]] (coincidentally, Genesis' former lead singer). It also made the number-one spot on ''[[The Village Voice]]'' critic [[Robert Christgau]]'s top 10 music videos in his year-end \"Dean's List\" feature, and number three on the equivalent list in his annual survey of music critics, [[Pazz & Jop]] (again losing out to \"Sledgehammer\").<ref>{{cite news|first= Robert |last= Christgau |title= Pazz & Jop 1986: Dean's List |date= 3 March 1987 |newspaper= [[The Village Voice]] |url= http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/pnj/deans86.php |accessdate= 13 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first= Robert |last= Christgau |title= The 1986 Pazz & Jop Critics Poll |date= 3 March 1987 |newspaper= [[The Village Voice]] |url= http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/pnj/pjres86.php |accessdate= 13 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Singles track listings==\n\n===7\": Virgin / GENS 3 (UK) ===\n# \"Land of Confusion\" \u2013 4:45\n# \"Feeding the Fire\" \u2013 5:54\n\n=== 7\": Atlantic / 7-89336 (U.S.) ===\n# \"Land of Confusion\" (LP Version) \u2013 4:45\n# \"Feeding the Fire\" \u2013 5:54\n\n===12\": Virgin / GENS 3\u201312 (UK) ===\n# \"Land of Confusion\" (Extended Remix) \u2013 6:55\n# \"Land of Confusion\" \u2013 4:45\n# \"Feeding the Fire\" \u2013 5:54\n\n===12\": Virgin / 608 632-213 (Germany) ===\n# \"Land of Confusion\" (Extended Remix) \u2013 6:55\n# \"Land of Confusion\" \u2013 4:45\n# \"Feeding the Fire\" \u2013 5:54\n\n===CD: Virgin / SNEG 3\u201312 (UK) ===\n# \"Land of Confusion\" \u2013 4:45\n# \"Land of Confusion\" (Extended Remix) \u2013 6:55\n# \"Feeding the Fire\" \u2013 5:54\n# \"Do the Neurotic\" \u2013 7:08\n\n===12\": Atlantic / PR 968 (U.S.) ===\n# \"Land of Confusion\" (Extended Remix) \u2013 6:55\n# \"Land of Confusion\" \u2013 4:45\n\n===7\": Atlantic / 7-89336 promo (U.S.) ===\n# \"Land of Confusion\" (Special Edited Remix) \u2013 3:53\n# \"Land of Confusion\" (Album Version) \u2013 4:45\n\n* Remixes by John Potoker\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!Chart (1986\u20131987)\n!Peak<br/>position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref>{{cite book|first= David |last= Kent |authorlink= David Kent (historian) |title= Australian Chart Book 1970\u20131992 |publisher= Australian Chart Book |location= [[St Ives, New South Wales|St Ives, N.S.W.]] |year= 1993 |isbn= 0-646-11917-6}}</ref>\n|21\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|27|artist=Genesis|song=Land Of Confusion|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 June 2016}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|14|artist=Genesis|song=Land Of Confusion|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 June 2016}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadatopsingles|8|chartid=0775|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 June 2016}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Finland ([[The Official Finnish Charts|Suomen virallinen lista]])<ref>{{cite book|first= Jake |last= Nyman |title= Suomi soi 4: Suuri suomalainen listakirja |year= 2005 |edition= 1st |publisher= Tammi |location= Helsinki |isbn= 951-31-2503-3 |language= fi}}</ref>\n|18\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany2|7|artist=Genesis|song=Land Of Confusion|songid=1556|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 June 2016}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Ireland2|9|song=Land of Confusion|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 June 2016}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch40|8|artist=Genesis Land Of Confusion|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 June 2016}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|10|artist=Genesis|song=Land Of Confusion|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 June 2016}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|9|artist=Genesis|song=Land Of Confusion|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 June 2016}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Sweden|10|artist=Genesis|song=Land Of Confusion|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 June 2016}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Switzerland|8|artist=Genesis|song=Land Of Confusion|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 June 2016}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UK|14|date=19861228|accessdate=13 June 2016|rowheader=true|refname=\"UK\"}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''Billboard'' [[Mainstream Rock (chart)|Album Rock Tracks]]<ref name=\"awards\"/>\n|11\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref name=\"awards\">{{cite web|title= Genesis \u2013 Awards |website= [[AllMusic]] |url= http://www.allmusic.com/artist/genesis-mn0000199995/awards |accessdate= 13 June 2016}}</ref>\n|4\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]]''<ref>{{cite magazine|title= CASH BOX Top 100 Singles \u2013 Week ending JANUARY 31, 1987 |magazine= [[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]] |url= http://cashboxmagazine.com/archives/80s_files/19870131.html |archivedate= 6 October 2012 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20121006112804/http://cashboxmagazine.com/archives/80s_files/19870131.html}}</ref>\n|5\n|}\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!Chart (2019)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Poland|82|chartid=2997|year=2019|rowheader=true|accessdate=19 March 2019}}\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!Chart (1987)\n!Rank\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Canada Top Singles (''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'')<ref>{{cite magazine|title= Top 100 Singles of '87 |magazine= [[RPM (magazine)|RPM]] |volume= 47 |issue= 12 |date= 26 December 1987 |accessdate= 13 June 2016 |url= http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.0920&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.0920.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.0920}}</ref>\n|63\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Germany ([[GfK Entertainment Charts|Official German Charts]])<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.offiziellecharts.de/charts/single-jahr/for-date-1987 |title= Jahrescharts \u2013 1987 |publisher= Offiziellecharts.de. GfK Entertainment Charts |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150509001159/https://www.offiziellecharts.de/charts/single-jahr/for-date-1987 |archivedate= 9 May 2015 |language= de}}</ref>\n|57\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Netherlands ([[Dutch Top 40]])<ref>{{cite web|title= Top 100-Jaaroverzicht van 1987 |publisher= [[Dutch Top 40]] |accessdate= 13 June 2016 |url= http://www.top40.nl/bijzondere-lijsten/top-100-jaaroverzichten/1987 |language= nl}}</ref>\n|95\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref>{{cite web|title= Top 100 Hits for 1987 |publisher= The Longbored Surfer |accessdate= 13 June 2016 |url= http://longboredsurfer.com/charts/1987}}</ref>\n|40\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Live performances==\nThe song was played on their ''[[Invisible Touch]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title= Invisible Touch |publisher= Genesis-movement.org |url= http://www.genesis-movement.org/php/listtour.php?tourid=15&addcommentsall= |accessdate= 13 June 2016}}</ref> ''[[We Can't Dance|The Way We Walk]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title= We Can't Dance |publisher= Genesis-movement.org |url= http://www.genesis-movement.org/php/listtour.php?tourid=16&addcommentsall= |accessdate= 13 June 2016}}</ref> ''[[Calling All Stations]]''<ref>{{cite web|title= Calling All Stations |publisher= Genesis-movement.org |url= http://www.genesis-movement.org/php/listtour.php?tourid=17&addcommentsall= |accessdate= 13 June 2016}}</ref> (with [[Ray Wilson (musician)|Ray Wilson]] on vocals) and ''[[Turn It On Again: The Tour]]''<ref>{{cite web|title= Studio & Misc |publisher= Genesis-movement.org |url= http://www.genesis-movement.org/php/listtour.php?tourid=18&addcommentsall= |accessdate= 13 June 2016}}</ref> tours, though later transposed to a lower key to accommodate Collins' deepening voice.\n\nIt also appears on their live albums ''[[The Way We Walk, Volume One: The Shorts]]'', and ''[[Live over Europe 2007]]''. As well as on their DVDs ''[[Live at Wembley Stadium (Genesis DVD)|Live at Wembley Stadium]]'', ''[[The Way We Walk - Live in Concert]]'' and ''[[When in Rome 2007]]''.{{Citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\n==Disturbed version {{anchor|Disturbed song and video}}==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Land of Confusion\n| cover      = disturbed_land_of_confusion.png\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Disturbed (band)|Disturbed]]\n| album      = [[Ten Thousand Fists]]\n| released   = 2006\n| format     =\n* [[Compact disc]]\n* [[Phonograph record|12\" picture LP]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Nu metal]]<ref>{{cite magazine|first= Eleanor |last= Goodman |title= The top 10 best Disturbed songs |magazine= [[Metal Hammer]] |date= 25 August 2016 |accessdate= 29 November 2018 |url= https://www.loudersound.com/features/the-top-10-best-disturbed-songs}}</ref>\n| length     = 4:47\n| label      = [[Reprise Records|Reprise]]\n| writer     =\n* [[Mike Rutherford]]\n* [[Tony Banks (musician)|Tony Banks]]\n* [[Phil Collins]]\n| producer   = [[Johnny K]]\n| prev_title = [[Just Stop]]\n| prev_year  = 2006\n| next_title = [[Ten Thousand Fists (song)|Ten Thousand Fists]]\n| next_year  = 2006\n}}\nThe American [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] band [[Disturbed (band)|Disturbed]] released a cover of the song on their third studio album, ''[[Ten Thousand Fists]]''. The song became the fourth single from that album. Vocalist [[David Draiman]] commented that the aim of covering the song was \"taking a song that's absolutely nothing like us and making it our own.\"<ref>{{cite web|title= DISTURBED Frontman: 'I See Ourselves As Being A Three-Decade Spanning Band' |publisher= [[Blabbermouth.net]] |date= 23 November 2006 |accessdate= 13 June 2016 |url= http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/disturbed-frontman-i-see-ourselves-as-being-a-three-decade-spanning-band/}}</ref> The line \"And the sound of your laughter\" in the original's bridge was replaced by \"In the wake of this madness,\" while the bridge of the song was replaced with a short solo by guitarist [[Dan Donegan]].\n\nIt was accompanied by a music video animated by [[Todd McFarlane]], known as the creator of the comics series ''[[Spawn (comics)|Spawn]]''. McFarlane had previously animated the music videos for the songs \"[[Freak on a Leash]]\" by [[Korn]] and \"[[Do the Evolution]]\" by [[Pearl Jam]]. According to McFarlane, the music video is \"a big view of the corporate world and how it all ties into just one big beast for me... The world is run by one giant thing, which is driven by greed and lust.\"<ref name=\"MTV\">{{cite news|first= Chris |last= Harris |title= Todd McFarlane to Make Genesis' 'Confusion' Clip Even More Disturbed |date= 10 March 2006 |publisher= [[MTV News]]. [[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]] |url= http://www.mtv.com/news/1525848/todd-mcfarlane-to-make-genesis-confusion-clip-even-more-disturbed/ |accessdate= 13 June 2016}}</ref> \"Land of Confusion\" reached No. 1 in the [[Mainstream Rock (chart)|Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks]]; making it Disturbed's first No. 1 single on that chart.\n\n===Music video===\nThe video starts out with [[Disturbed (band)#Mascot|The Guy]], Disturbed's mascot, falling to earth. It then shows military forces bearing the symbol of a [[dollar sign]]<ref name=\"MTV\"/> within a [[Flag of Germany#Nazi Germany and World War II (1933\u20131945)|circle of white within a field of red]], followed by legions of [[Blackshirts|black-clad soldiers]] reminiscent of [[Adolf Hitler]]'s [[Schutzstaffel]].<ref name=\"Khouri\">{{cite web|first= Andy |last= Khouri |title= CCI, Day 3: McFarlane Vs Kirkman? |date= 22 July 2006 |accessdate= 18 December 2008 |publisher= Comic Book Resources |url= http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=7666}}</ref> The video then shows the Guy, escaping bondage from chains, as the military forces continue to assault cities and civilians. Later on, leaders of various nations of the world (bearing close physical resemblance to [[George W. Bush]], [[Vladimir Putin]], [[Jacques Chirac]], [[Junichir\u014d Koizumi]] and [[Tony Blair]]) are shown sitting at a table with the same dollar sign on it. Eventually, the Guy confronts the soldiers, and leads the people in rebellion. Flags of several powerful nations are then shown, with the final flag sporting the dollar sign. The Guy leads the rebels to the [[headquarters of the United Nations]]<ref name=\"Khouri\"/> where they disrupt a meeting of the U.N. representatives. The Guy then leads the angry mob into a back room where they confront the real [[power behind the throne]], a gigantic, bloated [[Fat cat (term)|Fat Cat]]. The mob then drags him to the ground and once immobilized, the Guy destroys the Fat Cat, who explodes into a shower of dollar bills.\n\n===UK enhanced version===\n# \"Land of Confusion\"\n# \"Sickened\"\n# \"Land of Confusion\" <small>(video)</small>\n\n===UK, European and US vinyl 12\" limited edition picture disc===\n# \"Land of Confusion\"\n# \"Sickened\"\n\n===European version===\n# \"Land of Confusion\" <small>(version 1)</small>\n# \"Land of Confusion\" <small>(version 2)</small>\n\n===Personnel===\n* [[David Draiman]] \u2013 lead vocals\n* [[Dan Donegan]] \u2013 guitars, [[electronics]]\n* [[John Moyer]] \u2013 bass guitar, backing vocals\n* [[Mike Wengren]] \u2013 drums\n\n==Charts==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (2006)\n!Peak<br/>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|United Kingdom|79|date=2006-10-08|accessdate=13 June 2016}}\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' [[Mainstream Rock (chart)|Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks]]<ref name=\"awards2\">{{cite web|title= Disturbed \u2013 Awards |publisher= [[AllMusic]]. [[All Media Network]] |url= http://www.allmusic.com/artist/disturbed-mn0000175579/awards |accessdate= 13 June 2016}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' [[Alternative Songs|Modern Rock Tracks]]<ref name=\"awards2\"/>\n|align=\"center\"|18\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Billboard Mainstream Rock number-one songs of the 2000s#2006|List of Billboard Mainstream Rock number-one songs of the 2000s]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{YouTube|Yq7FKO5DlV0|\"Genesis - Land Of Confusion\"}}\n*{{YouTube|YV4oYkIeGJc|\"Disturbed - Land Of Confusion\"}}\n\n{{Genesis}}\n{{Disturbed}}\n\n[[Category:1986 songs]]\n[[Category:1986 singles]]\n[[Category:2006 singles]]\n[[Category:Billboard Mainstream Rock number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Benito Mussolini]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Diana, Princess of Wales]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Margaret Thatcher]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Michael Jackson]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Mikhail Gorbachev]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Muammar Gaddafi]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Pope John Paul II]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Richard Nixon]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Ruhollah Khomeini]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Ronald Reagan]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Bill Cosby]]\n[[Category:Disturbed (band) songs]]\n[[Category:Genesis (band) songs]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award for Best Concept Music Video]]\n[[Category:Music videos featuring puppetry]]\n[[Category:Animated music videos]]\n[[Category:Protest songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Hugh Padgham]]\n[[Category:Songs about nuclear war and weapons]]\n[[Category:Songs about Ronald Reagan]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Mike Rutherford]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Phil Collins]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Tony Banks (musician)]]\n[[Category:Spitting Image]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=June 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2014}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Land of Confusion\n| cover      = Genesis-Land-of-confusion-single-cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = Original single cover parodying 1963's ''[[With the Beatles]]''\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Genesis (band)|Genesis]]\n| album      = [[Invisible Touch]]\n| B-side     = Feeding the Fire\n| released   = 1986\n| format     =\n* [[Phonograph record|7\"]]\n* [[Twelve-inch single|12\"]]\n* [[CD single|CD]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Pop rock]]<ref>{{cite web|first= Dodie |last= Miller-Gould |title= \"Land of Confusion\" by Disturbed one of the best covers of a Genesis song |website= LemonWire |date= 19 April 2018 |accessdate= 16 January 2019 |url= https://lemonwire.com/2018/04/19/land-of-confusion-by-disturbed-one-of-the-best-cover-songs/ |quote= The tribal drums and the keyboard or synthesizer effects way off on the treble side of the soundscape give the song a nuanced feel that shows it as more than just a heavy metal song that used to be a pop-rock song.}}</ref>\n| length     = 4:45\n| label      =\n* [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]] {{small|US}}\n* [[Virgin Records|Virgin]] {{small|UK}}\n| writer     =\n* [[Mike Rutherford]]\n* [[Tony Banks (musician)|Tony Banks]]\n* [[Phil Collins]]\n| producer   =\n* [[Genesis (band)|Genesis]]\n* [[Hugh Padgham]]\n| prev_title = [[In Too Deep (Genesis song)|In Too Deep]]\n| prev_year  = 1986\n| next_title = [[Tonight, Tonight, Tonight]]\n| next_year  = 1987\n| misc       = \n{{Audio sample\n | type       = single\n | file       = GenesisLandofConfusion.ogg\n}}\n}}\n\"'''Land of Confusion'''\" is a song by the English rock band [[Genesis (band)|Genesis]] from their 1986 album ''[[Invisible Touch]]''. The song was the third track on the album and was the third track released as a single, reaching No. 4 in the U.S.<ref name=\"awards\"/> and No. 14 in the UK in late 1986.<ref name=\"UK\"/> It also reached No. 8 in the [[Netherlands]]. The music was written by the band, while the lyrics were written by guitarist [[Mike Rutherford]].<ref>{{cite web|first= Anil |last= Prasad |title= Genesis: Turning it on again |work= Innerviews |accessdate= 27 May 2012 |url= http://www.innerviews.org/inner/genesis.html}}</ref> The song's video featured puppets from the 1980s UK sketch show ''[[Spitting Image]]''.\n\n==Music video==\n{{Original research|section|date=September 2017}}\n[[File:LandofConfusionscreenshot1.JPG|left|250px|thumb|The band members (Banks, Collins and Rutherford) as they appeared in the video.]]\nThe song is widely remembered for its music video, which had heavy airplay on [[MTV]]. The video features [[caricature]] puppets by the British television show ''[[Spitting Image]]''. After [[Phil Collins]] saw a caricatured version of himself on the show, he commissioned the show's creators, [[Peter Fluck]] and [[Roger Law]], to create puppets of the entire band, as well as all the characters in the video.\n\nThe video opens with a caricatured [[Ronald Reagan]] (voiced by [[Chris Barrie]]), [[Nancy Reagan]], and a monkey, going to bed at 4:30 PM. Nancy is absorbed in reading ''His Way'', [[Kitty Kelley]]'s unauthorized biography of [[Frank Sinatra]]. Reagan, holding a teddy bear, kisses the monkey goodnight and goes to sleep and begins to have a nightmar], which sets the premise for the entire video. The video intermittently features a line of stomping feet, illustrating an army marching through a swamp, and they pick up heads of [[Cold War]]-era political figures in the swamp along the way.\n\nCaricatured versions of the band members are shown playing instruments on stage during a concert: [[Tony Banks (musician)|Tony Banks]] on an array of synthesizers (as well as a cash register full of cookies), [[Mike Rutherford]] on a [[Multi-neck guitar|four-necked guitar]], and two Phil Collins puppets: one on the drums, and one singing.\n\nDuring the second verse, the video features various world leaders giving speeches on large video screens in front of mass crowds; the video shows [[Benito Mussolini]], [[Ruhollah Khomeini|Ayatollah Khomeini]], [[Mikhail Gorbachev]] and his aides, and [[Muammar Gaddafi]]. Meanwhile, Reagan is shown putting on a [[Superman]] suit, fumbling along the way, while Collins sings,\n\n<blockquote><poem>\nOh Superman where are you now\nWhen everything's gone wrong somehow\nThe men of steel, the men of power\nAre losing control by the hour.\n</poem></blockquote>\n\nMeanwhile, the \"real world\" Reagan is shown blowing bubbles in a puddle of his own sweat (at one point, a rubber duck floats by).\n\nDuring the bridge, the Superman-costumed Reagan and a dinosaur (with punk jewellery) watch a television showing various clips (apparently from the ''Spitting Image'' show itself), including [[Johnny Carson]], [[Walter Cronkite]], [[Richard Nixon]], [[Leonard Nimoy]] as Mr. [[Spock]] (with a [[Rubik's Cube]]), and [[Bob Hope]]. This segues into a sequence apparently set in prehistoric times, where the two dinosaurs (one wearing a bow-tie) meet up with Ron and Nancy Reagan and a rather outlandish mammal eats an egg and reads a newspaper. At the end of this part, the chimpanzee from the prologue is shown throwing a bone in the air.\n\nAs the bone begins to fall there is a sudden switch to Collins catching a falling phone which he uses to inform the person on the other end that he \"won't be coming home tonight, my generation will put it right\" (which is when a caricature of a 1980s [[Pete Townshend]] is seen playing a chord on guitar and giving a thumb-up and on the \"we're not just making promises\" verse the bone lands (on top of [[David Bowie]] and [[Bob Dylan]], but misses [[Mick Jagger]]). Reagan is then shown riding a dinosaur through the streets while wearing a cowboy hat and wardrobe. As the video nears its climax, there are periodic scenes of a large group of spoofed celebrity puppets, including [[Tina Turner]], [[Michael Jackson]], [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], [[Prince (musician)|Prince]], [[Bill Cosby]], [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth]], [[Princess Diana]] and [[Hulk Hogan]] singing along to the chorus of the song, with [[Pope John Paul II]] playing an electric guitar.\n\nAt the end of the video, Reagan awakens from his dream, and surfaces from the sweat surrounding him; Nancy at this point is wearing a [[Snorkeling|snorkel]]. After taking a drink (missing his mouth and, indeed, his face, afflicting him with \"[[Alcoholism|drinking problems]]\", [[wikt:Special:Search/a la|\u00e0 la]] ''[[Airplane!]]''), he fumbles for a button next to his bed. He intends to push the one labelled \"Nurse\", but instead presses the one titled \"[[Nuclear weapon|Nuke]]\", setting off a nuclear explosion. Reagan then replies: \"That's one heck of a nurse!\" Nancy whacks him over the head with her snorkel.\n\nThe video, directed by John Lloyd and Jim Yukich, and produced by Jon Blair, won the short-lived [[Grammy Award]] for [[Grammy Award for Best Concept Music Video#Recipients|Best Concept Music Video]] during the [[30th Annual Grammy Awards#Award winners|30th Annual Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|title= Grammy Awards \u2013 1987 |website= [[Dotdash|About.com]] |url= http://80music.about.com/library/grammy/bl_1987.htm |archivedate= 21 September 2005 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20050921002536/http://80music.about.com/library/grammy/bl_1987.htm}}</ref> The video was also nominated for an [[MTV Video Music Award for Video of the Year]] in 1987, but lost to \"[[Sledgehammer (Peter Gabriel song)|Sledgehammer]]\" by [[Peter Gabriel]] (coincidentally, Genesis' former lead singer). It also made the number-one spot on ''[[The Village Voice]]'' critic [[Robert Christgau]]'s top 10 music videos in his year-end \"Dean's List\" feature, and number three on the equivalent list in his annual survey of music critics, [[Pazz & Jop]] (again losing out to \"Sledgehammer\").<ref>{{cite news|first= Robert |last= Christgau |title= Pazz & Jop 1986: Dean's List |date= 3 March 1987 |newspaper= [[The Village Voice]] |url= http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/pnj/deans86.php |accessdate= 13 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first= Robert |last= Christgau |title= The 1986 Pazz & Jop Critics Poll |date= 3 March 1987 |newspaper= [[The Village Voice]] |url= http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/pnj/pjres86.php |accessdate= 13 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Singles track listings==\n\n===7\": Virgin / GENS 3 (UK) ===\n# \"Land of Confusion\" \u2013 4:45\n# \"Feeding the Fire\" \u2013 5:54\n\n=== 7\": Atlantic / 7-89336 (U.S.) ===\n# \"Land of Confusion\" (LP Version) \u2013 4:45\n# \"Feeding the Fire\" \u2013 5:54\n\n===12\": Virgin / GENS 3\u201312 (UK) ===\n# \"Land of Confusion\" (Extended Remix) \u2013 6:55\n# \"Land of Confusion\" \u2013 4:45\n# \"Feeding the Fire\" \u2013 5:54\n\n===12\": Virgin / 608 632-213 (Germany) ===\n# \"Land of Confusion\" (Extended Remix) \u2013 6:55\n# \"Land of Confusion\" \u2013 4:45\n# \"Feeding the Fire\" \u2013 5:54\n\n===CD: Virgin / SNEG 3\u201312 (UK) ===\n# \"Land of Confusion\" \u2013 4:45\n# \"Land of Confusion\" (Extended Remix) \u2013 6:55\n# \"Feeding the Fire\" \u2013 5:54\n# \"Do the Neurotic\" \u2013 7:08\n\n===12\": Atlantic / PR 968 (U.S.) ===\n# \"Land of Confusion\" (Extended Remix) \u2013 6:55\n# \"Land of Confusion\" \u2013 4:45\n\n===7\": Atlantic / 7-89336 promo (U.S.) ===\n# \"Land of Confusion\" (Special Edited Remix) \u2013 3:53\n# \"Land of Confusion\" (Album Version) \u2013 4:45\n\n* Remixes by John Potoker\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!Chart (1986\u20131987)\n!Peak<br/>position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref>{{cite book|first= David |last= Kent |authorlink= David Kent (historian) |title= Australian Chart Book 1970\u20131992 |publisher= Australian Chart Book |location= [[St Ives, New South Wales|St Ives, N.S.W.]] |year= 1993 |isbn= 0-646-11917-6}}</ref>\n|21\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|27|artist=Genesis|song=Land Of Confusion|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 June 2016}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|14|artist=Genesis|song=Land Of Confusion|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 June 2016}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canadatopsingles|8|chartid=0775|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 June 2016}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Finland ([[The Official Finnish Charts|Suomen virallinen lista]])<ref>{{cite book|first= Jake |last= Nyman |title= Suomi soi 4: Suuri suomalainen listakirja |year= 2005 |edition= 1st |publisher= Tammi |location= Helsinki |isbn= 951-31-2503-3 |language= fi}}</ref>\n|18\n|-\n{{singlechart|Germany2|7|artist=Genesis|song=Land Of Confusion|songid=1556|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 June 2016}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Ireland2|9|song=Land of Confusion|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 June 2016}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch40|8|artist=Genesis Land Of Confusion|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 June 2016}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|10|artist=Genesis|song=Land Of Confusion|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 June 2016}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|9|artist=Genesis|song=Land Of Confusion|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 June 2016}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Sweden|10|artist=Genesis|song=Land Of Confusion|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 June 2016}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Switzerland|8|artist=Genesis|song=Land Of Confusion|rowheader=true|accessdate=13 June 2016}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UK|14|date=19861228|accessdate=13 June 2016|rowheader=true|refname=\"UK\"}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''Billboard'' [[Mainstream Rock (chart)|Album Rock Tracks]]<ref name=\"awards\"/>\n|11\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref name=\"awards\">{{cite web|title= Genesis \u2013 Awards |website= [[AllMusic]] |url= http://www.allmusic.com/artist/genesis-mn0000199995/awards |accessdate= 13 June 2016}}</ref>\n|4\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]]''<ref>{{cite magazine|title= CASH BOX Top 100 Singles \u2013 Week ending JANUARY 31, 1987 |magazine= [[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]] |url= http://cashboxmagazine.com/archives/80s_files/19870131.html |archivedate= 6 October 2012 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20121006112804/http://cashboxmagazine.com/archives/80s_files/19870131.html}}</ref>\n|5\n|}\n{|class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!Chart (2019)\n!Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Poland|82|chartid=2997|year=2019|rowheader=true|accessdate=19 March 2019}}\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!Chart (1987)\n!Rank\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Canada Top Singles (''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'')<ref>{{cite magazine|title= Top 100 Singles of '87 |magazine= [[RPM (magazine)|RPM]] |volume= 47 |issue= 12 |date= 26 December 1987 |accessdate= 13 June 2016 |url= http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.0920&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.0920.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.0920}}</ref>\n|63\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Germany ([[GfK Entertainment Charts|Official German Charts]])<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.offiziellecharts.de/charts/single-jahr/for-date-1987 |title= Jahrescharts \u2013 1987 |publisher= Offiziellecharts.de. GfK Entertainment Charts |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150509001159/https://www.offiziellecharts.de/charts/single-jahr/for-date-1987 |archivedate= 9 May 2015 |language= de}}</ref>\n|57\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Netherlands ([[Dutch Top 40]])<ref>{{cite web|title= Top 100-Jaaroverzicht van 1987 |publisher= [[Dutch Top 40]] |accessdate= 13 June 2016 |url= http://www.top40.nl/bijzondere-lijsten/top-100-jaaroverzichten/1987 |language= nl}}</ref>\n|95\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref>{{cite web|title= Top 100 Hits for 1987 |publisher= The Longbored Surfer |accessdate= 13 June 2016 |url= http://longboredsurfer.com/charts/1987}}</ref>\n|40\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Live performances==\nThe song was played on their ''[[Invisible Touch]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title= Invisible Touch |publisher= Genesis-movement.org |url= http://www.genesis-movement.org/php/listtour.php?tourid=15&addcommentsall= |accessdate= 13 June 2016}}</ref> ''[[We Can't Dance|The Way We Walk]]'',<ref>{{cite web|title= We Can't Dance |publisher= Genesis-movement.org |url= http://www.genesis-movement.org/php/listtour.php?tourid=16&addcommentsall= |accessdate= 13 June 2016}}</ref> ''[[Calling All Stations]]''<ref>{{cite web|title= Calling All Stations |publisher= Genesis-movement.org |url= http://www.genesis-movement.org/php/listtour.php?tourid=17&addcommentsall= |accessdate= 13 June 2016}}</ref> (with [[Ray Wilson (musician)|Ray Wilson]] on vocals) and ''[[Turn It On Again: The Tour]]''<ref>{{cite web|title= Studio & Misc |publisher= Genesis-movement.org |url= http://www.genesis-movement.org/php/listtour.php?tourid=18&addcommentsall= |accessdate= 13 June 2016}}</ref> tours, though later transposed to a lower key to accommodate Collins' deepening voice.\n\nIt also appears on their live albums ''[[The Way We Walk, Volume One: The Shorts]]'', and ''[[Live over Europe 2007]]''. As well as on their DVDs ''[[Live at Wembley Stadium (Genesis DVD)|Live at Wembley Stadium]]'', ''[[The Way We Walk - Live in Concert]]'' and ''[[When in Rome 2007]]''.{{Citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\n==Disturbed version {{anchor|Disturbed song and video}}==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Land of Confusion\n| cover      = disturbed_land_of_confusion.png\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Disturbed (band)|Disturbed]]\n| album      = [[Ten Thousand Fists]]\n| released   = 2006\n| format     =\n* [[Compact disc]]\n* [[Phonograph record|12\" picture LP]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Nu metal]]<ref>{{cite magazine|first= Eleanor |last= Goodman |title= The top 10 best Disturbed songs |magazine= [[Metal Hammer]] |date= 25 August 2016 |accessdate= 29 November 2018 |url= https://www.loudersound.com/features/the-top-10-best-disturbed-songs}}</ref>\n| length     = 4:47\n| label      = [[Reprise Records|Reprise]]\n| writer     =\n* [[Mike Rutherford]]\n* [[Tony Banks (musician)|Tony Banks]]\n* [[Phil Collins]]\n| producer   = [[Johnny K]]\n| prev_title = [[Just Stop]]\n| prev_year  = 2006\n| next_title = [[Ten Thousand Fists (song)|Ten Thousand Fists]]\n| next_year  = 2006\n}}\nThe American [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] band [[Disturbed (band)|Disturbed]] released a cover of the song on their third studio album, ''[[Ten Thousand Fists]]''. The song became the fourth single from that album. Vocalist [[David Draiman]] commented that the aim of covering the song was \"taking a song that's absolutely nothing like us and making it our own.\"<ref>{{cite web|title= DISTURBED Frontman: 'I See Ourselves As Being A Three-Decade Spanning Band' |publisher= [[Blabbermouth.net]] |date= 23 November 2006 |accessdate= 13 June 2016 |url= http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/disturbed-frontman-i-see-ourselves-as-being-a-three-decade-spanning-band/}}</ref> The line \"And the sound of your laughter\" in the original's bridge was replaced by \"In the wake of this madness,\" while the bridge of the song was replaced with a short solo by guitarist [[Dan Donegan]].\n\nIt was accompanied by a music video animated by [[Todd McFarlane]], known as the creator of the comics series ''[[Spawn (comics)|Spawn]]''. McFarlane had previously animated the music videos for the songs \"[[Freak on a Leash]]\" by [[Korn]] and \"[[Do the Evolution]]\" by [[Pearl Jam]]. According to McFarlane, the music video is \"a big view of the corporate world and how it all ties into just one big beast for me... The world is run by one giant thing, which is driven by greed and lust.\"<ref name=\"MTV\">{{cite news|first= Chris |last= Harris |title= Todd McFarlane to Make Genesis' 'Confusion' Clip Even More Disturbed |date= 10 March 2006 |publisher= [[MTV News]]. [[Viacom (2005\u2013present)|Viacom]] |url= http://www.mtv.com/news/1525848/todd-mcfarlane-to-make-genesis-confusion-clip-even-more-disturbed/ |accessdate= 13 June 2016}}</ref> \"Land of Confusion\" reached No. 1 in the [[Mainstream Rock (chart)|Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks]]; making it Disturbed's first No. 1 single on that chart.\n\n===Music video===\nThe video starts out with [[Disturbed (band)#Mascot|The Guy]], Disturbed's mascot, falling to earth. It then shows military forces bearing the symbol of a [[dollar sign]]<ref name=\"MTV\"/> within a [[Flag of Germany#Nazi Germany and World War II (1933\u20131945)|circle of white within a field of red]], followed by legions of [[Blackshirts|black-clad soldiers]] reminiscent of [[Adolf Hitler]]'s [[Schutzstaffel]].<ref name=\"Khouri\">{{cite web|first= Andy |last= Khouri |title= CCI, Day 3: McFarlane Vs Kirkman? |date= 22 July 2006 |accessdate= 18 December 2008 |publisher= Comic Book Resources |url= http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=7666}}</ref> The video then shows the Guy, escaping bondage from chains, as the military forces continue to assault cities and civilians. Later on, leaders of various nations of the world (bearing close physical resemblance to [[George W. Bush]], [[Vladimir Putin]], [[Jacques Chirac]], [[Junichir\u014d Koizumi]] and [[Tony Blair]]) are shown sitting at a table with the same dollar sign on it. Eventually, the Guy confronts the soldiers, and leads the people in rebellion. Flags of several powerful nations are then shown, with the final flag sporting the dollar sign. The Guy leads the rebels to the [[headquarters of the United Nations]]<ref name=\"Khouri\"/> where they disrupt a meeting of the U.N. representatives. The Guy then leads the angry mob into a back room where they confront the real [[power behind the throne]], a gigantic, bloated [[Fat cat (term)|Fat Cat]]. The mob then drags him to the ground and once immobilized, the Guy destroys the Fat Cat, who explodes into a shower of dollar bills.\n\n===UK enhanced version===\n# \"Land of Confusion\"\n# \"Sickened\"\n# \"Land of Confusion\" <small>(Video)</small>\n\n===UK, European and US vinyl 12\" limited edition picture disc===\n# \"Land of Confusion\"\n# \"Sickened\"\n\n===European version===\n# \"Land of Confusion\" <small>(Version 1)</small>\n# \"Land of Confusion\" <small>(Version 2)</small>\n\n===Personnel===\n* [[David Draiman]] \u2013 lead vocals\n* [[Dan Donegan]] \u2013 guitars, [[electronics]]\n* [[John Moyer]] \u2013 bass guitar, backing vocals\n* [[Mike Wengren]] \u2013 drums\n\n==Charts==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (2006)\n!Peak<br/>position\n|-\n{{singlechart|United Kingdom|79|date=2006-10-08|accessdate=13 June 2016}}\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' [[Mainstream Rock (chart)|Hot Mainstream Rock Tracks]]<ref name=\"awards2\">{{cite web|title= Disturbed \u2013 Awards |publisher= [[AllMusic]]. [[All Media Network]] |url= http://www.allmusic.com/artist/disturbed-mn0000175579/awards |accessdate= 13 June 2016}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|1\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' [[Alternative Songs|Modern Rock Tracks]]<ref name=\"awards2\"/>\n|align=\"center\"|18\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Billboard Mainstream Rock number-one songs of the 2000s#2006|List of Billboard Mainstream Rock number-one songs of the 2000s]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{YouTube|Yq7FKO5DlV0|\"Genesis - Land Of Confusion\"}}\n*{{YouTube|YV4oYkIeGJc|\"Disturbed - Land Of Confusion\"}}\n\n{{Genesis}}\n{{Disturbed}}\n\n[[Category:1986 songs]]\n[[Category:1986 singles]]\n[[Category:2006 singles]]\n[[Category:Billboard Mainstream Rock number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Benito Mussolini]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Diana, Princess of Wales]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Margaret Thatcher]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Michael Jackson]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Mikhail Gorbachev]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Muammar Gaddafi]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Pope John Paul II]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Richard Nixon]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Ruhollah Khomeini]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Ronald Reagan]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Bill Cosby]]\n[[Category:Disturbed (band) songs]]\n[[Category:Genesis (band) songs]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award for Best Concept Music Video]]\n[[Category:Music videos featuring puppetry]]\n[[Category:Animated music videos]]\n[[Category:Protest songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Hugh Padgham]]\n[[Category:Songs about nuclear war and weapons]]\n[[Category:Songs about Ronald Reagan]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Mike Rutherford]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Phil Collins]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Tony Banks (musician)]]\n[[Category:Spitting Image]]\n", "name_user": "Urgal", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDisturbed version {{anchor|Disturbed song and video}}", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Land_of_Confusion"}
