{"title_page": "2019 Latin American protests", "text_new": "{{merge|Latin American Spring|discuss=Talk:2019 Latin American protests#Merger proposal|date=January 2020}}\n{{Context|date=February 2020}}\n{{POV|date=January 2020}}\n{{short description|Latin American Spring}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox civil conflict\n| title            = 2019 Latin America protests  \n| subtitle         = \n| partof           = [[Latin American Spring]]\n| image            = {{Photomontage\n|photo1a = Manifestaciones en La Paz, Bolivia en contra el fraude electoral y el gobierno de Evo Morales.jpg \n|photo2a = Venezuelan protests - 23 January 2019.jpg\n|photo2b = Marcha Mas Grande De Chile 2019 Plaza Baquedano Drone.jpg\n|photo3a = Marchas 21N-Cali, Colombia (2).jpg\n|photo3b = Protestas en Ecuador 1.jpg\n|position = center \n| size = 260\n| color = #F5F5F5\n| border = 2\n| color_border = black\n| spacing = 3\n| foot_montage =  \n}}\n| caption          = Demonstrations in [[La Paz]], [[Bolivia]] on October 23, 2019; Action of workers in Cali, Colombia during the National strike on November 21;Crowds gather in the city of Santiago, [[Chile]] on October 25, 2019; Demonstrators in [[Quito]], [[Ecuador]]; \nDemonstrators gather in [[Caracas]], [[Venezuela]] on January 23, 2019\n| date             = 10 January 2019 \u2013 30 December 2019\n| place            = '''[[Latin America]]'''{{collapsible list\n|title=<center>'''particularly:'''</center>\n|1={{flag|Bolivia}}\n|2={{flag|Chile}}\n|3={{flag|Colombia}}\n|4={{flag|Ecuador}}\n|5={{flag|Guatemala}}\n|6={{flag|Haiti}}\n|7={{flag|Puerto Rico}}<br />[[2019 Latin American protests#Affected countries|and others]]</center>\n}}\n| coordinates      = \n| causes           = *[[Austerity]]\n*[[Income inequality]]\n*[[Privatization]]\n*[[Political corruption]]\n*[[Political scandals]]\n| goals            =\n*[[Democracy]]\n*[[Regime change]]\n*[[Reform]]\n*End to [[austerity]]\n*End to [[political corruption]]\n| methods          = *[[Civil disobedience]]\n*[[Civil resistance]]\n*[[Demonstration (protest)|Demonstrations]]\n*[[Internet activism]]\n*[[Mutiny]] \n*[[Protest]]s\n*[[Riot]]s\n*[[Social media]] activism \n*[[Strike action]]s\n*[[Urban warfare]]\n*[[Rebellion|Uprising]]\n| status           = ''Ongoing''\n| result           = \n| side1            = \n| side2            = \n| side3            = \n| side4            = \n| leadfigures1     = \n| leadfigures2     = \n| leadfigures3     = \n| leadfigures4     = \n| howmany1         = \n| howmany2         = \n| howmany3         = \n| howmany4         = \n| casualties1      = \n| casualties2      = \n| casualties3      = \n| casualties4      = \n| fatalities       = 192\n| injuries         = 6,088\n| arrests          = 11,099\n| detentions       =\n| charged          =\n| fined            =\n| casualties_label = \n| notes            = \n| sidebox          = \n{{Campaignbox 2019 South American protests}}\n}}\n \nThe 2019 Latin American protests correspond to a series of protests all over [[Latin America]] that coincided in 2019, and that is part of a larger context of international contestation movements since the end of 2018. Some of these protests continued into 2020. \n\nThere are various reasons for the emergence of these waves of protests, but all were anti-governments protests aiming to pressuring leaders to respond to the common concerns of citizens.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://latinamericareports.com/2019-a-year-in-protests/3953/|title=2019: A year in protests|last=Jenner|first=Frances|date=2019-12-12|website=Latin America Reports|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> Protests were triggered by a build-up of perceived antisocial government actions negatively impacting citizens, particularly financially, during a period of austerity following early-2000s prosperity across Latin America. The influence to protest at such large scales has been suggested to come from a widespread fear of economic and social crises caused by government actions, and dissatisfaction at political responses. This fear may be influenced by the [[crisis in Venezuela]].<ref name=\"Bloomberg\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-10-20/political-risk-revived-in-latin-america-as-protests-spread|title=Political Risk Is Revived in Latin America as Protests Spread|last=Spinetto|first=Juan Pablo|date=20 October 2019|website=Bloomberg L.P.|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs a result, Venezuela kicked off uprisings in Haiti, followed by Ecuador, Chile, Bolivia and Colombia mainly.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opendemocracy.net/en/democraciaabierta/2019-movilizaciones-ciudadanas-y-cambios-disruptivos-en-am%C3%A9rica-latina-en/|title=2019: Protests and disruptive changes in Latin America|website=openDemocracy|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>{{disputed inline|date=April 2020}} Though developing separately throughout the year, by October these protests were occurring routinely across several Latin American countries, in some cases widespread and riotous, like in Chile. \n\n''[[The Guardian]]'' discussed different opinions on whether the wave of protests constituted a \"Latin American spring\".<ref name=\"guardianphillips\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/oct/24/latin-american-spring-protests-chile-ecuador-bolivia-haiti|title=An explosion of protest, a howl of rage \u2013 but not a Latin American spring|last=Phillips|first=Tom|date=24 October 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=27 October 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> By November 2019, media outlets were using the term more widely.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/a-government-chased-from-its-capital-a-president-forced-into-exile-a-storm-of-protest-rages-in-south-america/2019/11/14/897f85ba-0651-11ea-9118-25d6bd37dfb1_story.html|title=How to make sense of the many protests raging across South America|last=Faiola|first=Anthony|date=|website=Washington Post|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/41bd23fa9bb74ce5a1d3529ac3354e52|title=Morales' exit stymies comeback for Latin America's left|date=2019-11-12|website=AP NEWS|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldpoliticsreview.com/articles/28290/if-chile-can-erupt-over-inequality-anywhere-can|title=If Chile Can Erupt Over Inequality, Anywhere Can|last=|first=|date=|website=World Politics Review|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref> It is a wave of the greater [[Latin American Spring]] that has been causing unrest around the region since 2014.\n\n== Characteristics ==\nThere are two common interpretations regarding the protests. According to Brian Winter, policy vice president of the [[Americas Society]]/[[Council of the Americas]], main characteristics of the movement are economic dissatisfaction following the commodities boom and the reliance on military might, with Winter saying that Latin Americans perceive that [[Strongman (politics)|strongman politics]] leads to change.<ref name=\":3\" /> Dr. Lupu of the Latin American Public Opinion Project agreed that as corruption and socioeconomic issues increased in Latin America, citizens turn towards strongmen and distanced themselves from supporting democracy.<ref name=\":3\" /> Winter expressed concern with his assessment of Latin America in 2019, stating \"My fear is that we\u2019ve gone back to the battle days of coups and protests and instability ... I think all of these things play a role and the takeaway could be that we\u2019re returning to a period ... where uprisings and coups and civil unrest were the rule of the day\".<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nHowever, that interpretation of the protests as a sign that Latin American countries are rejecting democracy is far from being common in the Spanish speaking countries, or even clearly majoritarian among scholars in English speaking countries. For many other experts, the main common characteristics of the protests are the opposite to the ones stated in the previous paragraph. This second line of experts claim that the main characteristics of the 2019 Latin American protests are the rejection of the current economic model and a desire to pressure for political reforms to make the governments of the region more democratic and representative, not less. Among other authors in this line, the following can be mentioned. [[Michael Shifter]], president of the [[Inter-American Dialogue]], states that what is happening is a \"rebellion against the elites in Latin America\", motivated by a \"widespread sentiment of dissatisfaction and lack of fairness\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Shifter|first=Michael|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/21/opinion/international-world/latin-america-elites-protests.html|title=Opinion {{!}} The Rebellion Against the Elites in Latin America|date=2020-01-21|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-03|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> [[Noam Chomsky]] calls the Chilean protests \"very inspiring and very appropriate\", because the \"[[Neoliberalism|Neoliberal]] assault against much of the population of the world pretty much began in Chile\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3Qy4Df28ohU|title=Chomsky on Chile`s demonstrations|last=Chomsky|first=Noam|date=Jan 3, 2020|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 3, 2020}}</ref> Salim Vally, professor at the University of Johannesburg, remembers in an article about the role of educator that, though the protests were \"heavily repressed, it did not stop two million people from flooding the streets. Their collective proclamation is best captured by the words on a popular placard \u2013 \u2018Neoliberalism was born in Chile and will die in Chile\u2019 \".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.universityworldnews.com/post.php?story=20191209120619834|title=The role of educators in the fight against neoliberalism|website=University World News|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> Oscar Guardiola-Rivera, senior lecturer in law at the [[University of London]], states \"The \u2018risk to democracy\u2019 in Chile isn\u2019t from protesters. It\u2019s from [[Sebasti\u00e1n Pi\u00f1era|Pi\u00f1era]] and the 1%\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Guardiola-Rivera|first=Oscar|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/oct/24/democracy-chile-protesters-pinera-pinochet|title=The \u2018risk to democracy\u2019 in Chile isn\u2019t from protesters. It\u2019s from Pi\u00f1era and the 1% {{!}} Oscar Guardiola-Rivera|date=2019-10-24|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-03|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>  [[Enric Gonz\u00e1lez]] calls the protests \"an insurrection of the youth\" in the most online-read newspaper in Spanish, [[El Pa\u00eds]], and claims that \"Chilean students are the stars of the movie in the insurrection against the social model inherited from Pinochet\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Gonz\u00e1lez|first=Enric|url=https://elpais.com/internacional/2019/11/23/actualidad/1574543096_923129.html|title=La revoluci\u00f3n de los muchachos|date=2019-11-24|work=El Pa\u00eds|access-date=2020-03-03|language=es|issn=1134-6582}}</ref> [[Jorge Casta\u00f1eda Gutman]], former Mexican Secretary of Foreign Affairs and currently professor at [[New York University]], claims that the protests are fueled by \"economic and democratic hopes\", because the protestors have \"achieved a certain consumer status,\" but at the same time they find themselves in a situation regarding public services, healthcare, education costs, and democratic representation that, according to Casta\u00f1eda, \"sounds a lot like the United States.... what a lot of people in the United States are also clamoring for\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/11/12/778451923/economic-and-democratic-hopes-fuel-protests-in-latin-america|title=Economic And Democratic Hopes Fuel Protests In Latin America|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nHistorically, Latin America has seen two such similar periods of unified protests: during [[Latin American debt crisis|severe austerity in the 1980s]] and again during economic and political crises from 1998 to 2002.<ref name=\"guardianphillips\" /> \n\nValeska Hesse, director of the Latin America office of the [[Friedrich Ebert Foundation]], suggested that the \"social trends\" leading to protesting in certain areas of Latin America were consistent throughout many countries in the region.<ref name=\"DW\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/south-americas-protests-fueled-by-extreme-social-inequality/a-50977566|title=South America's protests fueled by 'extreme' social inequality|date=26 October 2019|website=Deutsche Welle|url-status=live|access-date=27 October 2019}}</ref> Deutsche Welle describes one of these risk factors as the \"extreme inequality between rich and poor [that] can be seen in many countries across the continent\", noting that Latin American countries occupy eight of the top ten spots in the list of most economically unequal.<ref name=\"DW\" /> \n\nMany observers, however, suggest that the strongest cause of protests, and a unifying element unique to Latin America, is a period of economic downturn and/or instability following a boom in the early years of the 21st century; they report that though Latin America comprises countries of varying wealth and political leanings, its shared regional history gives this protest-fueling background.<ref name=\"DW\" /><ref name=\"guardianphillips\" /><ref name=\"AP\">{{cite web|url=https://apnews.com/957b27f2ca9441bda64e60a441517a5a|title=Is boom, then slump, behind fiery Latin American protests?|last=|first=|date=24 October 2019|website=AP News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Bloomberg\" />  \n\nOn another side, Mac Margolis, in an opinion piece for Bloomberg, suggests that many of the nations fall into this category but that Chile, with a reasonably stable economic history, does not, instead positing a different connecting factor in what he describes as a \"willful [[technocracy]]\" seen among all of Latin America's leaders; he explains that they use international economic advice to implement measures with short-term detriments, and respond negatively to public questioning.<ref name=\"margolis\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2019-10-23/chile-s-protests-aren-t-like-other-latin-american-protests|title=Opinion {{!}} Chile's Protests Aren't Like Other Latin American Protests|last=Margolis|first=Mac|date=23 October 2019|editor-last=Gibney|editor-first=James|website=Bloomberg L.P.|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 October 2019}}</ref> Margolis also discusses \"[h]arsh fiscal measures and feckless management\", and \"a bum economy and a widening gap between poverty and plenty\" as causes for protests across Latin America, exempting Chile.<ref name=\"margolis\" /> \n\nMichael Alvarez, a spokesperson for the [[Heinrich B\u00f6ll Foundation]], also suggests that there was an improvement in social equality alongside that of the economy, and that this has equally slumped, saying that \"people in Latin America are no longer willing to accept social inequality\".<ref name=\"DW\" /> An expert speaking to Deutsche Welle also suggested that an aim of the protests is more social destabilization than seeking any true improvements, a theory rejected by other experts.<ref name=\"DW\" />\n\n[[Michael Reid (journalist)|Michael Reid]] proposed the economic nosedive as the cause of protests, but told ''The Guardian'' that the region was more complex, noting this as only the first of three catalysts; the others are \"public rage against Latin America's political machine after a wave of corruption scandals that have discredited traditional political elites, sparked furious protests in countries including Peru and Haiti, and propelled a new generation of populists to power in Brazil and Mexico\" and for certain \"radical\" protestors emerging in Ecuador and Chile also the dedication of the [[yellow vests movement]] and the \"frontliners\", a group of 20 police fighters in [[2019 Hong Kong protests|Hong Kong]].<ref name=\"guardianphillips\" />  \n\nThe various commenters on the wave of protests also present the belief that while several of the protests were triggered for diverse and seemingly trivial reasons, these trigger points were considered the final straw in a build-up of small actions of perceived mismanagement and repression;<ref name=\"guardianphillips\" /><ref name=\"margolis\" /><ref name=\"AP\" /><ref name=\"Bloomberg\" /> [[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]] appends in particular that \"Latin America has a history of exploding unrest when prices go up for essential services and products, which are often subsidized and subject to price distortions\".<ref name=\"Bloomberg\" />    \n\nColombian experts criticize the statements from leaders in countries of protest which suggest that Venezuelan and Cuban meddling is deliberately sowing unrest across the region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/americas/venezuela-has-no-role-in-latin-america-protests-expert/1626472|title=Venezuela has no role in Latin America protests: expert|website=www.aa.com.tr|access-date=2019-10-28}}</ref> In October, disputed Venezuelan president [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] claimed that he influenced protests and that \"the plan is going exactly as [they] hoped\" to destabilize \"all of Latin America and the Caribbean\".<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/central-america-caribbean/2019-10-29/why-latin-america-was-primed-explode|title=Why Latin America Was Primed to Explode|last=Na\u00edm|first=Mois\u00e9s|date=2019-11-13|access-date=2019-11-23|last2=Winter|first2=Brian|language=en-US|issn=0015-7120}}</ref> Commenters describe this as an attempt to appear more powerful than he really is as Venezuela began mass protests again.<ref name=\":1\" />   \n\n== World context ==\nOne of the Latin American protests, the beginnings of the movement in Chile, has been linked by a commenter to [[Protests of 2019|contemporary protests around the world]], such as the [[2019 Arab protests]] and [[2019 Hong Kong protests]]. Several of the protests around the world are fueled by austerity following the [[Financial crisis of 2007\u201308|2008 crisis]] (which did not affect South America), perceived corruption, lack of democratic representation, difficulties among the younger generations, a monopoly on resources by the elite, and increase in costs.<ref name=\"nyt20191023\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/23/world/middleeast/global-protests.html|title=From Chile to Lebanon, Protests Flare Over Wallet Issues|last=Walsh|first=Declan|date=2019-10-23|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-12-05|last2=Fisher|first2=Max|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>{{Relevance inline|date=December 2019}}  \n\n== Protest actions ==\nThe Associated Press described protests within the wave as having the key signature of [[arson]], as well as often being more violent than typical.<ref name=\"AP\" /> Despite differing levels of economic and social security, the protests are the same in all countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/07f0e09e-0795-11ea-9afa-d9e2401fa7ca|title=Latin America faces a second 'lost decade'|last=|first=|date=|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref>\n\n== Affected countries ==\n[[File:Cartography of Latin America.svg|thumb|Map of Latin American countries]]\nReports agree that protests in [[2018\u201319 Haitian protests|Haiti]], [[2019 Ecuadorian protests|Ecuador]], and [[2019 Bolivian protests|Bolivia]] are certainly within the Latin American wave.{{Efn|As in [a] and other sources.|name=|group=}} The first incidence of violence was reported in Haiti on 11 February with 4 people getting killed on the first day of the anti government riots.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vaticannews.va/en/world/news/2019-02/haiti-protesters-call-for-president-resignation.html|title=Deadly anti-government riots rock Haiti - Vatican News|date=2019-02-11|website=www.vaticannews.va|language=en|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref> Most also definitively include [[2019 Chilean protests|Chile]]; it is attached only tentatively by Mac Margolis.<ref name=\"margolis\" /> Margolis also lists 2019 protests in Honduras and Argentina as part of the wave;<ref name=\"margolis\" /> Valeska Hesse discounts Argentina prior to [[2019 Argentine general election|27 October]],<ref name=\"DW\" /> though it is included by Bloomberg because of \"voters revolt[ing] against President [[Mauricio Macri|Mauricio Macri']]<nowiki/>s budget-cutting agenda\" in the summer.<ref name=\"Bloomberg\" /> Within Latin American media,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.batimes.com.ar/news/latin-america/protests-engulf-latin-america-but-dont-oversimplify-experts-say.phtml|title=Protests engulf Latin America, but don't oversimplify, experts say|last=Graf|first=Carly|date=27 October 2019|website=Buenos Aires Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref> Peru, Puerto Rico, and Guatemala<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/world/americas/article236358643.html|title=Latin America awash in troubles amid protests, uprisings and a distracted Washington|last=Wyss|first=Jim|last2=Charles|first2=Jacqueline|date=17 October 2019|website=Miami Herald|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref> have been included in accounts of the wave.\n\nReports on the wave of protests sometimes exclude the [[2019 Venezuelan protests|2019 protests in Venezuela]].{{Efn|For example, Venezuela's issues are mentioned in the Associated Press article about the wave of protests, but only as a direct source for issues in Haiti.<ref name=AP/>|name=|group=}} Similarly, protests occurred in [[Brazil]] through 2019, but were mostly challenging the government's environmental policies during the [[2019 Amazon rainforest wildfires]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/aug/24/brazilian-protesters-bolsonaro-amazon-fires|title=Brazilian protesters rail against Bolsonaro as Amazon fires rage on|last=Phillips|first=Dom|date=2019-08-24|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-11-22|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In light of the other nearby protests, Brazilian congressman [[David Miranda (politician)|David Miranda]] wrote in ''[[The Guardian]]'' in November that though people in the country have the same motivations, they recognize that protests would do harm in Brazil, as President [[Jair Bolsonaro]] would use unrest as justification to implement a military dictatorship.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/nov/21/bolsonaro-brazil-military-dictatorship-violence|title=Bolsonaro wants to end democracy in Brazil. Here's one way he could do it {{!}} David Miranda|last=Miranda|first=David|date=2019-11-21|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-11-22|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Before Mexico began protesting against unfair policies, it saw protests through the year, but these were part of the \"Glitter Revolution\" to denounce [[violence against women]] in the country.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/aug/26/desperation-and-rage-mexican-women-take-to-streets-to-protest-unabated-sexual-violence-glitter-revolution|title=Mexico's 'glitter revolution' targets violence against women|last=Phillips|first=Tom|date=2019-08-26|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-11-23|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5717205/mexico-women-protests/|title=Demonstrators in Mexico Protest the Daily Killing of Women and Girls|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://merionwest.com/2019/08/22/mexicos-glitter-revolution-how-should-women-protest/|title=Mexico's Glitter Revolution: How Should Women Protest?|date=2019-08-22|website=Merion West|language=en|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref>\n\nStudent protests broke out in [[Colombia]] after a September corruption scandal; in mid-November these protests grew into larger public strikes, influenced by the protests nearby.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://thecitypaperbogota.com/bogota/as-colombia-faces-a-nationwide-strike-nov-21-why-are-students-protesting/23208|title=As Colombia faces nationwide strike Nov.21, why are students protesting?|last=Bhaumik|first=Sanoja|date=2019-11-18|website=The City Paper Bogot\u00e1|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref> When hundreds of thousands of people began protesting in Chile and Colombia, generally peaceful and safe countries in Latin America, in October and November 2019, respectively, it was asserted that the protests across the continent are of the same mindset and triggered by each other; commenters suggested that after Chile, it was likely the entire region would soon follow.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/with-nationwide-strike-colombia-joins-south-americas-season-of-protest/2019/11/21/2d3adf0e-0bef-11ea-8054-289aef6e38a3_story.html|title=With nationwide strike, Colombia joins South America's season of protest|last=|first=|date=21 November 2019|website=[[The Washington Post]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=22 November 2019}}</ref>  \n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!\n!Jan\n!Feb\n!Mar\n!Apr\n!May\n!Jun\n!Jul\n!Aug\n!Sep\n!Oct\n!Nov\n!Dec\n|-\n|'''[[2019 Venezuelan protests|Venezuela]]'''\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n|\n|-\n|'''Guatemala'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/world/la-fg-guatemala-protests-20190114-story.html|title=Thousands of Guatemalans protest in support of anti-corruption commission|date=2019-01-14|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nbcphiladelphia.com/news/politics/Activists-Protest-Guatemala-US-Migrant-Asylum-Pact-513302371.html|title=Guatemalan Activists Protest Migrant Asylum Pact With US|last=Figueroa|first=Sonny|website=NBC 10 Philadelphia|language=en|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/09/guatemala-congress-approves-state-siege-protests-190908014110498.html|title=Guatemala's congress approves state of siege despite protests|last=|first=|date=|website=Al Jazeera|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pri.org/stories/2019-10-14/guatemala-shut-down-its-anti-corruption-commission-now-its-people-worry-about|title=Guatemala shut down its anti-corruption commission. Now its people worry about impunity.|website=Public Radio International|language=en|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref>{{clarify|date=November 2019}}\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n|\n|-\n|'''[[2018\u201319 Haitian protests|Haiti]]'''\n|\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| \n| \n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| \n|\n|-\n|'''[[2018\u20132019 Nicaraguan protests|Nicaragua]]'''\n|\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Cura\u00e7ao'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20190222-venezuela-sea-aid-bid-puts-quiet-curacao-spotlight|title=Venezuela sea aid bid puts quiet Curacao in spotlight|date=2019-02-22|website=France 24|language=en|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref>\n|\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Belize'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.breakingbelizenews.com/2019/04/12/protests-underway-outside-house-in-belmopan/|title=Protests underway outside House in Belmopan|date=2019-04-12|website=Breaking Belize News-The Leading Online News Source of Belize|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Paraguay'''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/22/world/americas/paraguay-corruption.html|title=In Paraguay, Fighting Graft With Eggs and Toilet Paper|last=Londo\u00f1o|first=Ernesto|date=2019-04-22|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-11-22|last2=Carneri|first2=Santi|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-paraguay-president-idUSKCN1V421O|title=Paraguayan president's popularity plummets amid Brazil-linked political crisis|date=2019-08-14|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-11-22|language=en}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Honduras'''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-48712001|title=Army deployed in Honduras after violent protests|last=|first=|date=2019-06-21|work=BBC|access-date=2019-11-22|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/aug/07/honduras-protesters-president-juan-orlando-hernandez-riot-police|title=Honduras protesters calling on president to quit clash with riot police|last=Reuters|first=|date=7 August 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=28 October 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/videos/2019-10-25/protests-in-honduras-turn-violent-video|title=Protests in Honduras Turn Violent|last=|first=|date=25 October 2019|website=Bloomberg L.P.|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| \n|\n|-\n|'''Guyana'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pridenews.ca/2019/07/19/guyanas-main-opposition-stage-protest-rumoured-house-house-registration/|title=Guyana's Main Opposition Stage Protest Against Rumoured House-To-House Registration|date=2019-07-19|website=Pride News|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://guyanatimesgy.com/guyanese-protests-guyanas-illegal-govt/|title=Guyanese protest Guyana's illegal Govt|date=2019-09-20|website=Guyana Times|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Argentina'''<ref>{{Citation|last=|first=|title=Argentines protest in Buenos Aires against Macri's policies|date=28 August 2019|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BkdTJCsb2KU|volume=|pages=|publisher=Agence France Press|access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/09/situation-dire-argentinians-protest-food-crisis-190913062627019.html|title='The situation is dire': Argentines protest over food crisis|last=|first=|date=13 September 2019|website=Al Jazeera|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| \n|\n|-\n|'''[[Telegramgate|Puerto Rico]]'''\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n|style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| \n| \n|\n|-\n|'''[[2017\u201319 Peruvian political crisis|Peru]]'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/01/world/peru-protests-vizcarra-congress-intl/index.html|title=Protests in Peru as country is thrown into political uncertainty|last=Dominguez|first=Claudia|last2=Lewis|first2=Aimee|date=1 October 2019|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| \n|\n|-\n|'''[[2019 Ecuadorian protests|Ecuador]]'''\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''[[2019 Chilean protests|Chile]]'''\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n|-\n|'''[[2019 Bolivian protests|Bolivia]]'''\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n|\n|-\n|'''[[2019 Colombian protests|Colombia]]'''\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n|style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Latin American Spring]]  \n*[[List of protests in the 21st century]]  \n*[[Latin American economy]]   \n*[[Pink tide]]  \n*[[Conservative wave]]   \n*[[Crisis in Venezuela]]    \n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}   \n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}  \n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.ft.com/content/a52b0124-f5b5-11e9-a79c-bc9acae3b654 Financial Times' weekly update]\n\n{{Ongoing protests}}  \n[[Category:2019 protests|Latin America]]\n[[Category:2019 in South America]]\n[[Category:Latin American Spring]]\n[[Category:Ongoing protests]]\n[[Category:2020 protests]]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2019-20_Latin_American_protests}}\n", "text_old": "{{merge|Latin American Spring|discuss=Talk:2019 Latin American protests#Merger proposal|date=January 2020}}\n{{Context|date=February 2020}}\n{{POV|date=January 2020}}\n{{short description|Latin American Spring}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox civil conflict\n| title            = 2019 Latin America protests  \n| subtitle         = \n| partof           = [[Latin American Spring]]\n| image            = {{Photomontage\n|photo1a = Manifestaciones en La Paz, Bolivia en contra el fraude electoral y el gobierno de Evo Morales.jpg \n|photo2a = Venezuelan protests - 23 January 2019.jpg\n|photo2b = Marcha Mas Grande De Chile 2019 Plaza Baquedano Drone.jpg\n|photo3a = Marchas 21N-Cali, Colombia (2).jpg\n|photo3b = Protestas en Ecuador 1.jpg\n|position = center \n| size = 260\n| color = #F5F5F5\n| border = 2\n| color_border = black\n| spacing = 3\n| foot_montage =  \n}}\n| caption          = Demonstrations in [[La Paz]], [[Bolivia]] on October 23, 2019; Action of workers in Cali, Colombia during the National strike on November 21;Crowds gather in the city of Santiago, [[Chile]] on October 25, 2019; Demonstrators in [[Quito]], [[Ecuador]]; \nDemonstrators gather in [[Caracas]], [[Venezuela]] on January 23, 2019\n| date             = 10 January 2019 \u2013 30 December 2019\n| place            = '''[[Latin America]]'''{{collapsible list\n|title=<center>'''particularly:'''</center>\n|1={{flag|Bolivia}}\n|2={{flag|Chile}}\n|3={{flag|Colombia}}\n|4={{flag|Ecuador}}\n|5={{flag|Guatemala}}\n|6={{flag|Haiti}}\n|7={{flag|Puerto Rico}}<br />[[2019 Latin American protests#Affected countries|and others]]</center>\n}}\n| coordinates      = \n| causes           = *[[Austerity]]\n*[[Income inequality]]\n*[[Privatization]]\n*[[Political corruption]]\n*[[Political scandals]]\n| goals            =\n*[[Democracy]]\n*[[Regime change]]\n*[[Reform]]\n*End to [[austerity]]\n*End to [[political corruption]]\n| methods          = *[[Civil disobedience]]\n*[[Civil resistance]]\n*[[Demonstration (protest)|Demonstrations]]\n*[[Internet activism]]\n*[[Mutiny]] \n*[[Protest]]s\n*[[Riot]]s\n*[[Social media]] activism \n*[[Strike action]]s\n*[[Urban warfare]]\n*[[Rebellion|Uprising]]\n| status           = ''Ongoing''\n| result           = \n| side1            = \n| side2            = \n| side3            = \n| side4            = \n| leadfigures1     = \n| leadfigures2     = \n| leadfigures3     = \n| leadfigures4     = \n| howmany1         = \n| howmany2         = \n| howmany3         = \n| howmany4         = \n| casualties1      = \n| casualties2      = \n| casualties3      = \n| casualties4      = \n| fatalities       = 192\n| injuries         = 6,088\n| arrests          = 11,099\n| detentions       =\n| charged          =\n| fined            =\n| casualties_label = \n| notes            = \n| sidebox          = \n{{Campaignbox 2019 South American protests}}\n}}\n \nThe 2019 Latin American protests correspond to a series of protests all over [[Latin America]] that coincided in 2019, and that is part of a larger context of international contestation movements since the end of 2018. Some of this protest continued into 2020. \n\nThere are various reasons for the emergence of these waves of protests, but all were anti-governments protests aiming to pressuring leaders to respond to the common concerns of citizens.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://latinamericareports.com/2019-a-year-in-protests/3953/|title=2019: A year in protests|last=Jenner|first=Frances|date=2019-12-12|website=Latin America Reports|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> Protests were triggered by a build-up of perceived antisocial government actions negatively impacting citizens, particularly financially, during a period of austerity following early-2000s prosperity across Latin America. The influence to protest at such large scales has been suggested to come from a widespread fear of economic and social crises caused by government actions, and dissatisfaction at political responses. This fear may be influenced by the [[crisis in Venezuela]].<ref name=\"Bloomberg\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-10-20/political-risk-revived-in-latin-america-as-protests-spread|title=Political Risk Is Revived in Latin America as Protests Spread|last=Spinetto|first=Juan Pablo|date=20 October 2019|website=Bloomberg L.P.|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs a result, Venezuela kicked off uprisings in Haiti, followed by Ecuador, Chile, Bolivia and Colombia mainly.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.opendemocracy.net/en/democraciaabierta/2019-movilizaciones-ciudadanas-y-cambios-disruptivos-en-am%C3%A9rica-latina-en/|title=2019: Protests and disruptive changes in Latin America|website=openDemocracy|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>{{disputed inline|date=April 2020}} Though developing separately throughout the year, by October these protests were occurring routinely across several Latin American countries, in some cases widespread and riotous, like in Chile. \n\n''[[The Guardian]]'' discussed different opinions on whether the wave of protests constituted a \"Latin American spring\".<ref name=\"guardianphillips\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/oct/24/latin-american-spring-protests-chile-ecuador-bolivia-haiti|title=An explosion of protest, a howl of rage \u2013 but not a Latin American spring|last=Phillips|first=Tom|date=24 October 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=27 October 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> By November 2019, media outlets were using the term more widely.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/a-government-chased-from-its-capital-a-president-forced-into-exile-a-storm-of-protest-rages-in-south-america/2019/11/14/897f85ba-0651-11ea-9118-25d6bd37dfb1_story.html|title=How to make sense of the many protests raging across South America|last=Faiola|first=Anthony|date=|website=Washington Post|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/41bd23fa9bb74ce5a1d3529ac3354e52|title=Morales' exit stymies comeback for Latin America's left|date=2019-11-12|website=AP NEWS|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldpoliticsreview.com/articles/28290/if-chile-can-erupt-over-inequality-anywhere-can|title=If Chile Can Erupt Over Inequality, Anywhere Can|last=|first=|date=|website=World Politics Review|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref> It is a wave of the greater [[Latin American Spring]] that has been causing unrest around the region since 2014.\n\n== Characteristics ==\nThere are two common interpretations regarding the protests. According to Brian Winter, policy vice president of the [[Americas Society]]/[[Council of the Americas]], main characteristics of the movement are economic dissatisfaction following the commodities boom and the reliance on military might, with Winter saying that Latin Americans perceive that [[Strongman (politics)|strongman politics]] leads to change.<ref name=\":3\" /> Dr. Lupu of the Latin American Public Opinion Project agreed that as corruption and socioeconomic issues increased in Latin America, citizens turn towards strongmen and distanced themselves from supporting democracy.<ref name=\":3\" /> Winter expressed concern with his assessment of Latin America in 2019, stating \"My fear is that we\u2019ve gone back to the battle days of coups and protests and instability ... I think all of these things play a role and the takeaway could be that we\u2019re returning to a period ... where uprisings and coups and civil unrest were the rule of the day\".<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nHowever, that interpretation of the protests as a sign that Latin American countries are rejecting democracy is far from being common in the Spanish speaking countries, or even clearly majoritarian among scholars in English speaking countries. For many other experts, the main common characteristics of the protests are the opposite to the ones stated in the previous paragraph. This second line of experts claim that the main characteristics of the 2019 Latin American protests are the rejection of the current economic model and a desire to pressure for political reforms to make the governments of the region more democratic and representative, not less. Among other authors in this line, the following can be mentioned. [[Michael Shifter]], president of the [[Inter-American Dialogue]], states that what is happening is a \"rebellion against the elites in Latin America\", motivated by a \"widespread sentiment of dissatisfaction and lack of fairness\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Shifter|first=Michael|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/01/21/opinion/international-world/latin-america-elites-protests.html|title=Opinion {{!}} The Rebellion Against the Elites in Latin America|date=2020-01-21|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-03|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> [[Noam Chomsky]] calls the Chilean protests \"very inspiring and very appropriate\", because the \"[[Neoliberalism|Neoliberal]] assault against much of the population of the world pretty much began in Chile\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3Qy4Df28ohU|title=Chomsky on Chile`s demonstrations|last=Chomsky|first=Noam|date=Jan 3, 2020|website=YouTube|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=March 3, 2020}}</ref> Salim Vally, professor at the University of Johannesburg, remembers in an article about the role of educator that, though the protests were \"heavily repressed, it did not stop two million people from flooding the streets. Their collective proclamation is best captured by the words on a popular placard \u2013 \u2018Neoliberalism was born in Chile and will die in Chile\u2019 \".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.universityworldnews.com/post.php?story=20191209120619834|title=The role of educators in the fight against neoliberalism|website=University World News|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> Oscar Guardiola-Rivera, senior lecturer in law at the [[University of London]], states \"The \u2018risk to democracy\u2019 in Chile isn\u2019t from protesters. It\u2019s from [[Sebasti\u00e1n Pi\u00f1era|Pi\u00f1era]] and the 1%\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Guardiola-Rivera|first=Oscar|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/oct/24/democracy-chile-protesters-pinera-pinochet|title=The \u2018risk to democracy\u2019 in Chile isn\u2019t from protesters. It\u2019s from Pi\u00f1era and the 1% {{!}} Oscar Guardiola-Rivera|date=2019-10-24|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-03|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>  [[Enric Gonz\u00e1lez]] calls the protests \"an insurrection of the youth\" in the most online-read newspaper in Spanish, [[El Pa\u00eds]], and claims that \"Chilean students are the stars of the movie in the insurrection against the social model inherited from Pinochet\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Gonz\u00e1lez|first=Enric|url=https://elpais.com/internacional/2019/11/23/actualidad/1574543096_923129.html|title=La revoluci\u00f3n de los muchachos|date=2019-11-24|work=El Pa\u00eds|access-date=2020-03-03|language=es|issn=1134-6582}}</ref> [[Jorge Casta\u00f1eda Gutman]], former Mexican Secretary of Foreign Affairs and currently professor at [[New York University]], claims that the protests are fueled by \"economic and democratic hopes\", because the protestors have \"achieved a certain consumer status,\" but at the same time they find themselves in a situation regarding public services, healthcare, education costs, and democratic representation that, according to Casta\u00f1eda, \"sounds a lot like the United States.... what a lot of people in the United States are also clamoring for\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/11/12/778451923/economic-and-democratic-hopes-fuel-protests-in-latin-america|title=Economic And Democratic Hopes Fuel Protests In Latin America|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>\n\n== Background ==\nHistorically, Latin America has seen two such similar periods of unified protests: during [[Latin American debt crisis|severe austerity in the 1980s]] and again during economic and political crises from 1998 to 2002.<ref name=\"guardianphillips\" /> \n\nValeska Hesse, director of the Latin America office of the [[Friedrich Ebert Foundation]], suggested that the \"social trends\" leading to protesting in certain areas of Latin America were consistent throughout many countries in the region.<ref name=\"DW\">{{cite web|url=https://www.dw.com/en/south-americas-protests-fueled-by-extreme-social-inequality/a-50977566|title=South America's protests fueled by 'extreme' social inequality|date=26 October 2019|website=Deutsche Welle|url-status=live|access-date=27 October 2019}}</ref> Deutsche Welle describes one of these risk factors as the \"extreme inequality between rich and poor [that] can be seen in many countries across the continent\", noting that Latin American countries occupy eight of the top ten spots in the list of most economically unequal.<ref name=\"DW\" /> \n\nMany observers, however, suggest that the strongest cause of protests, and a unifying element unique to Latin America, is a period of economic downturn and/or instability following a boom in the early years of the 21st century; they report that though Latin America comprises countries of varying wealth and political leanings, its shared regional history gives this protest-fueling background.<ref name=\"DW\" /><ref name=\"guardianphillips\" /><ref name=\"AP\">{{cite web|url=https://apnews.com/957b27f2ca9441bda64e60a441517a5a|title=Is boom, then slump, behind fiery Latin American protests?|last=|first=|date=24 October 2019|website=AP News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 October 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Bloomberg\" />  \n\nOn another side, Mac Margolis, in an opinion piece for Bloomberg, suggests that many of the nations fall into this category but that Chile, with a reasonably stable economic history, does not, instead positing a different connecting factor in what he describes as a \"willful [[technocracy]]\" seen among all of Latin America's leaders; he explains that they use international economic advice to implement measures with short-term detriments, and respond negatively to public questioning.<ref name=\"margolis\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/opinion/articles/2019-10-23/chile-s-protests-aren-t-like-other-latin-american-protests|title=Opinion {{!}} Chile's Protests Aren't Like Other Latin American Protests|last=Margolis|first=Mac|date=23 October 2019|editor-last=Gibney|editor-first=James|website=Bloomberg L.P.|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 October 2019}}</ref> Margolis also discusses \"[h]arsh fiscal measures and feckless management\", and \"a bum economy and a widening gap between poverty and plenty\" as causes for protests across Latin America, exempting Chile.<ref name=\"margolis\" /> \n\nMichael Alvarez, a spokesperson for the [[Heinrich B\u00f6ll Foundation]], also suggests that there was an improvement in social equality alongside that of the economy, and that this has equally slumped, saying that \"people in Latin America are no longer willing to accept social inequality\".<ref name=\"DW\" /> An expert speaking to Deutsche Welle also suggested that an aim of the protests is more social destabilization than seeking any true improvements, a theory rejected by other experts.<ref name=\"DW\" />\n\n[[Michael Reid (journalist)|Michael Reid]] proposed the economic nosedive as the cause of protests, but told ''The Guardian'' that the region was more complex, noting this as only the first of three catalysts; the others are \"public rage against Latin America's political machine after a wave of corruption scandals that have discredited traditional political elites, sparked furious protests in countries including Peru and Haiti, and propelled a new generation of populists to power in Brazil and Mexico\" and for certain \"radical\" protestors emerging in Ecuador and Chile also the dedication of the [[yellow vests movement]] and the \"frontliners\", a group of 20 police fighters in [[2019 Hong Kong protests|Hong Kong]].<ref name=\"guardianphillips\" />  \n\nThe various commenters on the wave of protests also present the belief that while several of the protests were triggered for diverse and seemingly trivial reasons, these trigger points were considered the final straw in a build-up of small actions of perceived mismanagement and repression;<ref name=\"guardianphillips\" /><ref name=\"margolis\" /><ref name=\"AP\" /><ref name=\"Bloomberg\" /> [[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]] appends in particular that \"Latin America has a history of exploding unrest when prices go up for essential services and products, which are often subsidized and subject to price distortions\".<ref name=\"Bloomberg\" />    \n\nColombian experts criticize the statements from leaders in countries of protest which suggest that Venezuelan and Cuban meddling is deliberately sowing unrest across the region.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aa.com.tr/en/americas/venezuela-has-no-role-in-latin-america-protests-expert/1626472|title=Venezuela has no role in Latin America protests: expert|website=www.aa.com.tr|access-date=2019-10-28}}</ref> In October, disputed Venezuelan president [[Nicol\u00e1s Maduro]] claimed that he influenced protests and that \"the plan is going exactly as [they] hoped\" to destabilize \"all of Latin America and the Caribbean\".<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.foreignaffairs.com/articles/central-america-caribbean/2019-10-29/why-latin-america-was-primed-explode|title=Why Latin America Was Primed to Explode|last=Na\u00edm|first=Mois\u00e9s|date=2019-11-13|access-date=2019-11-23|last2=Winter|first2=Brian|language=en-US|issn=0015-7120}}</ref> Commenters describe this as an attempt to appear more powerful than he really is as Venezuela began mass protests again.<ref name=\":1\" />   \n\n== World context ==\nOne of the Latin American protests, the beginnings of the movement in Chile, has been linked by a commenter to [[Protests of 2019|contemporary protests around the world]], such as the [[2019 Arab protests]] and [[2019 Hong Kong protests]]. Several of the protests around the world are fueled by austerity following the [[Financial crisis of 2007\u201308|2008 crisis]] (which did not affect South America), perceived corruption, lack of democratic representation, difficulties among the younger generations, a monopoly on resources by the elite, and increase in costs.<ref name=\"nyt20191023\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/23/world/middleeast/global-protests.html|title=From Chile to Lebanon, Protests Flare Over Wallet Issues|last=Walsh|first=Declan|date=2019-10-23|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-12-05|last2=Fisher|first2=Max|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>{{Relevance inline|date=December 2019}}  \n\n== Protest actions ==\nThe Associated Press described protests within the wave as having the key signature of [[arson]], as well as often being more violent than typical.<ref name=\"AP\" /> Despite differing levels of economic and social security, the protests are the same in all countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/07f0e09e-0795-11ea-9afa-d9e2401fa7ca|title=Latin America faces a second 'lost decade'|last=|first=|date=|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref>\n\n== Affected countries ==\n[[File:Cartography of Latin America.svg|thumb|Map of Latin American countries]]\nReports agree that protests in [[2018\u201319 Haitian protests|Haiti]], [[2019 Ecuadorian protests|Ecuador]], and [[2019 Bolivian protests|Bolivia]] are certainly within the Latin American wave.{{Efn|As in [a] and other sources.|name=|group=}} The first incidence of violence was reported in Haiti on 11 February with 4 people getting killed on the first day of the anti government riots.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vaticannews.va/en/world/news/2019-02/haiti-protesters-call-for-president-resignation.html|title=Deadly anti-government riots rock Haiti - Vatican News|date=2019-02-11|website=www.vaticannews.va|language=en|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref> Most also definitively include [[2019 Chilean protests|Chile]]; it is attached only tentatively by Mac Margolis.<ref name=\"margolis\" /> Margolis also lists 2019 protests in Honduras and Argentina as part of the wave;<ref name=\"margolis\" /> Valeska Hesse discounts Argentina prior to [[2019 Argentine general election|27 October]],<ref name=\"DW\" /> though it is included by Bloomberg because of \"voters revolt[ing] against President [[Mauricio Macri|Mauricio Macri']]<nowiki/>s budget-cutting agenda\" in the summer.<ref name=\"Bloomberg\" /> Within Latin American media,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.batimes.com.ar/news/latin-america/protests-engulf-latin-america-but-dont-oversimplify-experts-say.phtml|title=Protests engulf Latin America, but don't oversimplify, experts say|last=Graf|first=Carly|date=27 October 2019|website=Buenos Aires Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref> Peru, Puerto Rico, and Guatemala<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.miamiherald.com/news/nation-world/world/americas/article236358643.html|title=Latin America awash in troubles amid protests, uprisings and a distracted Washington|last=Wyss|first=Jim|last2=Charles|first2=Jacqueline|date=17 October 2019|website=Miami Herald|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref> have been included in accounts of the wave.\n\nReports on the wave of protests sometimes exclude the [[2019 Venezuelan protests|2019 protests in Venezuela]].{{Efn|For example, Venezuela's issues are mentioned in the Associated Press article about the wave of protests, but only as a direct source for issues in Haiti.<ref name=AP/>|name=|group=}} Similarly, protests occurred in [[Brazil]] through 2019, but were mostly challenging the government's environmental policies during the [[2019 Amazon rainforest wildfires]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/aug/24/brazilian-protesters-bolsonaro-amazon-fires|title=Brazilian protesters rail against Bolsonaro as Amazon fires rage on|last=Phillips|first=Dom|date=2019-08-24|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-11-22|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In light of the other nearby protests, Brazilian congressman [[David Miranda (politician)|David Miranda]] wrote in ''[[The Guardian]]'' in November that though people in the country have the same motivations, they recognize that protests would do harm in Brazil, as President [[Jair Bolsonaro]] would use unrest as justification to implement a military dictatorship.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2019/nov/21/bolsonaro-brazil-military-dictatorship-violence|title=Bolsonaro wants to end democracy in Brazil. Here's one way he could do it {{!}} David Miranda|last=Miranda|first=David|date=2019-11-21|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-11-22|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Before Mexico began protesting against unfair policies, it saw protests through the year, but these were part of the \"Glitter Revolution\" to denounce [[violence against women]] in the country.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/aug/26/desperation-and-rage-mexican-women-take-to-streets-to-protest-unabated-sexual-violence-glitter-revolution|title=Mexico's 'glitter revolution' targets violence against women|last=Phillips|first=Tom|date=2019-08-26|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-11-23|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5717205/mexico-women-protests/|title=Demonstrators in Mexico Protest the Daily Killing of Women and Girls|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://merionwest.com/2019/08/22/mexicos-glitter-revolution-how-should-women-protest/|title=Mexico's Glitter Revolution: How Should Women Protest?|date=2019-08-22|website=Merion West|language=en|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref>\n\nStudent protests broke out in [[Colombia]] after a September corruption scandal; in mid-November these protests grew into larger public strikes, influenced by the protests nearby.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://thecitypaperbogota.com/bogota/as-colombia-faces-a-nationwide-strike-nov-21-why-are-students-protesting/23208|title=As Colombia faces nationwide strike Nov.21, why are students protesting?|last=Bhaumik|first=Sanoja|date=2019-11-18|website=The City Paper Bogot\u00e1|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref> When hundreds of thousands of people began protesting in Chile and Colombia, generally peaceful and safe countries in Latin America, in October and November 2019, respectively, it was asserted that the protests across the continent are of the same mindset and triggered by each other; commenters suggested that after Chile, it was likely the entire region would soon follow.<ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/the_americas/with-nationwide-strike-colombia-joins-south-americas-season-of-protest/2019/11/21/2d3adf0e-0bef-11ea-8054-289aef6e38a3_story.html|title=With nationwide strike, Colombia joins South America's season of protest|last=|first=|date=21 November 2019|website=[[The Washington Post]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=22 November 2019}}</ref>  \n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!\n!Jan\n!Feb\n!Mar\n!Apr\n!May\n!Jun\n!Jul\n!Aug\n!Sep\n!Oct\n!Nov\n!Dec\n|-\n|'''[[2019 Venezuelan protests|Venezuela]]'''\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n|\n|-\n|'''Guatemala'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/world/la-fg-guatemala-protests-20190114-story.html|title=Thousands of Guatemalans protest in support of anti-corruption commission|date=2019-01-14|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nbcphiladelphia.com/news/politics/Activists-Protest-Guatemala-US-Migrant-Asylum-Pact-513302371.html|title=Guatemalan Activists Protest Migrant Asylum Pact With US|last=Figueroa|first=Sonny|website=NBC 10 Philadelphia|language=en|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/09/guatemala-congress-approves-state-siege-protests-190908014110498.html|title=Guatemala's congress approves state of siege despite protests|last=|first=|date=|website=Al Jazeera|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pri.org/stories/2019-10-14/guatemala-shut-down-its-anti-corruption-commission-now-its-people-worry-about|title=Guatemala shut down its anti-corruption commission. Now its people worry about impunity.|website=Public Radio International|language=en|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref>{{clarify|date=November 2019}}\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n|\n|-\n|'''[[2018\u201319 Haitian protests|Haiti]]'''\n|\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| \n| \n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| \n|\n|-\n|'''[[2018\u20132019 Nicaraguan protests|Nicaragua]]'''\n|\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Cura\u00e7ao'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.france24.com/en/20190222-venezuela-sea-aid-bid-puts-quiet-curacao-spotlight|title=Venezuela sea aid bid puts quiet Curacao in spotlight|date=2019-02-22|website=France 24|language=en|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref>\n|\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Belize'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.breakingbelizenews.com/2019/04/12/protests-underway-outside-house-in-belmopan/|title=Protests underway outside House in Belmopan|date=2019-04-12|website=Breaking Belize News-The Leading Online News Source of Belize|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-23}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Paraguay'''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/22/world/americas/paraguay-corruption.html|title=In Paraguay, Fighting Graft With Eggs and Toilet Paper|last=Londo\u00f1o|first=Ernesto|date=2019-04-22|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-11-22|last2=Carneri|first2=Santi|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-paraguay-president-idUSKCN1V421O|title=Paraguayan president's popularity plummets amid Brazil-linked political crisis|date=2019-08-14|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-11-22|language=en}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Honduras'''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-48712001|title=Army deployed in Honduras after violent protests|last=|first=|date=2019-06-21|work=BBC|access-date=2019-11-22|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/aug/07/honduras-protesters-president-juan-orlando-hernandez-riot-police|title=Honduras protesters calling on president to quit clash with riot police|last=Reuters|first=|date=7 August 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=28 October 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/videos/2019-10-25/protests-in-honduras-turn-violent-video|title=Protests in Honduras Turn Violent|last=|first=|date=25 October 2019|website=Bloomberg L.P.|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| \n|\n|-\n|'''Guyana'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pridenews.ca/2019/07/19/guyanas-main-opposition-stage-protest-rumoured-house-house-registration/|title=Guyana's Main Opposition Stage Protest Against Rumoured House-To-House Registration|date=2019-07-19|website=Pride News|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://guyanatimesgy.com/guyanese-protests-guyanas-illegal-govt/|title=Guyanese protest Guyana's illegal Govt|date=2019-09-20|website=Guyana Times|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-22}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''Argentina'''<ref>{{Citation|last=|first=|title=Argentines protest in Buenos Aires against Macri's policies|date=28 August 2019|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BkdTJCsb2KU|volume=|pages=|publisher=Agence France Press|access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/09/situation-dire-argentinians-protest-food-crisis-190913062627019.html|title='The situation is dire': Argentines protest over food crisis|last=|first=|date=13 September 2019|website=Al Jazeera|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| \n|\n|-\n|'''[[Telegramgate|Puerto Rico]]'''\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n|style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| \n| \n|\n|-\n|'''[[2017\u201319 Peruvian political crisis|Peru]]'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/10/01/world/peru-protests-vizcarra-congress-intl/index.html|title=Protests in Peru as country is thrown into political uncertainty|last=Dominguez|first=Claudia|last2=Lewis|first2=Aimee|date=1 October 2019|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 October 2019}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| \n|\n|-\n|'''[[2019 Ecuadorian protests|Ecuador]]'''\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''[[2019 Chilean protests|Chile]]'''\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n|-\n|'''[[2019 Bolivian protests|Bolivia]]'''\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n| style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n|\n|-\n|'''[[2019 Colombian protests|Colombia]]'''\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n|style=\"background: #FFB\" |\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Latin American Spring]]  \n*[[List of protests in the 21st century]]  \n*[[Latin American economy]]   \n*[[Pink tide]]  \n*[[Conservative wave]]   \n*[[Crisis in Venezuela]]    \n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}   \n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}  \n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.ft.com/content/a52b0124-f5b5-11e9-a79c-bc9acae3b654 Financial Times' weekly update]\n\n{{Ongoing protests}}  \n[[Category:2019 protests|Latin America]]\n[[Category:2019 in South America]]\n[[Category:Latin American Spring]]\n[[Category:Ongoing protests]]\n[[Category:2020 protests]]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2019-20_Latin_American_protests}}\n", "name_user": "SoleneTrevidic", "label": "safe", "comment": "Correction of grammar mistakes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019_Latin_American_protests"}
{"title_page": "Dunskey Castle", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=February 2017}}\n{{synthesis|date=February 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n[[Image:DUNSKEY CASTLE by Francis Grose, 1790.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Dunskey Castle by Francis Grose 1790.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/antiquitiesofsc02gros|title=The antiquities of Scotland|first=Francis|last=Grose|date=16 November 1797|publisher=London : Printed for Hooper & Wigstead ...|via=Internet Archive}}</ref>]]\n'''Dunskey Castle''' is a ruined, 12th century [[tower house]] or castle, located {{convert|0.5|mi|km}} south of the village of [[Portpatrick]], [[Rhinns]], Wigtownshire, on the south-west coast of [[Scotland]].<ref>Royal National Directory of Scotland.(1915) p.1368 https://archive.org/stream/slatersroyalnati1915dire#page/1368/mode/1up</ref>\n\nDunskey Castle is a [[scheduled monument]],<ref>{{Historic Environment Scotland|num=SM2017|desc=Dunskey Castle|access-date=27 March 2019}}</ref> a 'nationally important' [[archaeological site]] or historic building, given protection against unauthorised change.\n\n==Description==\nThe three-storey [[L-plan castle|L-plan]] structure is sited on a promontory, with a rock-cut ditch, {{convert|15|m|ft}} wide by {{convert|2.5|m|ft}} deep, defending the only access, from the north-east.<ref name=LBR>{{Historic Environment Scotland|num=LB16777|desc=Dunskey Castle|cat=A (removed)|access-date=27 March 2019|fewer-links=yes}}</ref> The castle measures {{convert|30|by|14.3|m|ft}}, with walls {{convert|1.5|m|ft}} thick, although the building is now a roofless shell. The north-east wing is of a later date, and the foundations of a south range are visible. Near the castle are the remains of a watchtower, {{convert|7|m|ft}} square, built on the cliff edge.<ref name=CANMORE>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rcahms.gov.uk/pls/portal/newcanmore.newcandig_details_gis?inumlink=60632 |title=Dunskey Castle, NMRS Number: NX05SW 3 |work=[[Canmore (database)|CANMORE]] |publisher=[[RCAHMS]] |accessdate=7 November 2008}}</ref> [[Timothy Pont]]'s map drawn c. 1580 \u2013 1590 shows Dunskay Castle with 2 watchtowers on the cliff edge fronting the sea.<ref>National Library of Scotland http://maps.nls.uk/atlas/blaeu/page.cfm?id=95</ref>  [[Francis Grose]]'s drawing dated show of 10 May 1790s the ruins of the foundations and sea-wall on the south and what looks to be the large entrance door in the southern corner from where the inside staircase may have led straight up to the new \"Hall\" built c.1520. Grose's drawing shows Ireland (approx. Island Magee / Larne area) in the background across the sea.<ref>\"The Antiquities of Scotland, volume 2, pp.191\u2013192, by Francis Grose, pub. 1791 by Hooper.  https://books.google.com/books?id=Ai0DAAAAYAAJ&q=Dunskey#v=snippet&q=Dunskey&f=false</ref>\n\nIn virtue of a tradition preserved in the [[Book of Leinster]], W. J. Watson identifies the place named in it as Port Rig (Portrie, Portree) with the later [[Portpatrick]], connecting 'Rig' with Reregonium, which he regards as the royal town of the Novantae and places in this region. He would thus carry [[Portpatrick]]'s history back to the first century of our era, while he dates a rather later reference to about AD 250.<ref>History of the Celtic Placenames of Scotland. {{cite web |url=http://www.spns.org.uk/watsdg.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-05-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140821230319/http://www.spns.org.uk/watsdg.html |archivedate=21 August 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Portpatrick was known as the port of Castle Dunskey.\n\nDunskey is undoubtedly romantic. It was a location for the 1951 film \"Kidnapped\" of Robert Louis Stevenson's novel, as well as for the 1952 film ''[[Hunted (film)|Hunted]]''.\n\nThe owner, Lady Amy McFall, restricts public access to the castle.\n\n==13th and 14th centuries==\nIn the 1290s, [[John Comyn, Earl of Buchan]], had a licence from [[Edward I of England]], reigned 1272\u20131307) to dig for lead in the Calf of Man (off the coast of the Isle of Man), to cover eight towers of the [[Cruggleton Castle]] / Crogiltoun Castle in Wigtownshire. Was Dunskey Castle built about this time ?<ref>Chalmer's Caledonia (vol. iii. p. 372), quoted by Cumming (History of the Isle of Man, p. 307)</ref> and in AD1291 the nearby [[Wigtown Castle]] was in the hands of the same Edward I who committed it to the charge of Walter de Currie or Cory / Corry / Coree (laird of Dunskey). King Edward I ultimately conferred [[Wigtown Castle]] (and Dunskey Castle ?) on [[John Balliol]] the Scottish King (reigned AD1292-1296 after which Scotland was without a monarch for 10 years and Sir William Wallace fought the English in 1297, but was defeated at Falkirk in 1298).<ref>The Edinburgh Encyclopedia, vol.18, p.521, by Sir David Brewster, published 1832 in Philadelphia by Joseph Parker.  https://books.google.com/books?id=O4wEAAAAYAAJ&q=Wigton#v=snippet&q=Wigton&f=false</ref>\n\nBy 10 October 1303 Walter de Corry was dead and his lands were taken into the King's hands (King Edward I of England).<ref>Fine Rolls, i 483</ref><ref>Dumfriesshire and Galloway \"Transactions and Journal of Proceedings\" Ed: R.C. Reid, pub.1916. Third Series, Vol. IV, p.30 Early History of the Corries</ref><ref>external link :  [http://www.dgnhas.org.uk/transonline/SerIII-Vol4.pdf] http://www.medievalgenealogy.org.uk/sources/rolls.shtml</ref><ref>Calendar of the Fine Rolls. Vol. I. Edward I. AD.1272\u20131307, p.483 (493 of 798 on external link, Brigham Young University Library copy</ref>\n\nOn 28 August 1296 the [[Ragman Rolls]] for Wigtownshire had been compiled at Berwick-on-Tweed, which time and place King Edward I of England also convened a Parliament of those\nScottish nobles summoned by him to attend at the border city. The Wigtownshire roll contained 26 names, and some who were later associated with Dunskey Castle were Thomas de KITHEHILT (Adair of Kinhilt / Kilhelt) ; Fergus MakDowylt (MacDowell) ; Thomas MacUlagh (MacCullough / McCullagh) ; Andrew (McDowell) de Logan ; Dougal MacDowly (MacDowell / McDowell) ; Gilbert de Hanneth (Hannay) ; William MacUlagh (MacCullough / McCullagh) ; Michel MacUlagh (MacCullough) ; Johan Seneschal (Stewart, from whom descended the Earls of Darnly and Lennox) ; [[Maria de Ergadia|Maria, Queen of Mann and the Isles]].<ref>Publication of The Bannatyne Club. page 145 (178 of 274).  https://www.scribd.com/doc/92560287/Ragman-Roll-Instrument-a-Public-a-00-Tho-Mu-Oft</ref>\n\nc. AD1326  \"Index of Charters, &c. by King Robert I.\" King Robert I  [[Robert the Bruce]] (born 1274 reigned AD1306-1329 after the Interregnum AD1296-1306). p.&nbsp;27 \"In the Roll of Robert the First, marked on the back with this mark, X.  1. Carta to Thomas Edzear (probably Adair) of the lands of Kildonan, in the Rynes, Wigtoun\".<ref>An Index, drawn up about the year 1629 of many Records of Charters, granted between the years 1309 and 1413, by William Robertson, Esq. Edinburgh. p.27.  https://archive.org/details/indexdrawnupabou00grea</ref>\n\nAnother version of Adair / Odeir / Edzear of Dunskey Castle in Portry / Portrie / Port-N-Rye, is :  c. AD1326  \"Index A.  From old vol. XXII Fol. 25 verso \u2013 Ane Littill small skine quahirin ar conteinet certane complaintis of deforcementis and of haldingis of landis quhilkis ar decydit be the parliament. Carta Thomas Odeir de terris de Kildonan Dromin Porthie\" [ Portrie = Dunsky & Kinhilt ].<ref>Register of the Great Seal of Scotland. vol.1 AD1306-1424 p.555, Appendix 2. no.681</ref> c.1600 Kildonan Castle appeared to be a large castle just east of Dunskey Castle, shown on [[Timothy Pont]]'s map in Blaeu's Atlas.<ref>National Library Scotland, Blaeu Atlas. http://maps.nls.uk/atlas/blaeu/page.cfm?id=95</ref>\n\n==15th & 16th centuries==\nOn 10 November 1426 Nigello Adare de Portar (Portrie \u2013 Dunskey) was a witness to the restoration of the lands of Lochnaw [[Lochnaw Castle]], by Willelmi de Douglas, dom. de [[Leswalt]] to Andree Agnew.<ref>Registrum magni sigilli regum Scotorum, Vol. II. AD1424-1513, page 40, no.183. https://archive.org/stream/registrummagnisi02scot#page/40/mode/2up</ref>  This Nigello Adare may have died prior AD1456.\n\nIn AD 1456 [[Gilbert Kennedy, 1st Lord Kennedy]] of Dunure obtained the ward of Kynhilt (with Dunskey Castle) as shown in [[Exchequer Rolls of Scotland]], Kennedy \u2013 Gilbert of DUNURE \"OBTAINS ward of Kynhilt\" (Dunskey) see 208 & 347.<ref>[[Exchequer Rolls of Scotland]], vol. VI index p.730</ref> It is interesting that R.M.S. vol. II index on p.&nbsp;1134 BALLIVUS de Carrick, lists p.&nbsp;94 no.414, 13 February 1450 Gilbert Kennedy of Dunure \"REX confirmavit Gilberto Kenedy de Dunure consang. suo, \u2013 quod ipse Gilbertus et heredes sui masculi essent caput totius progeniei sue tam in calumpniis quam in aliis articulis et negotiis ad KENKYNOLL pertinere valentibus; unaetum officio ballivi comitatus de Carric et hominum ipsius dectione et cum armorum ostensione in omnibus, sub comite de Carric qui pro tempore fuerit ; \u2013 que idem Gilb. personaliter resignavit.\" iv. 182.<ref>Register of the Great Seal of Scotland. vol. II, index on p.1134</ref> \u2013 was he a bailie & Kenkynol, as Exchequer Roll AD1455 shows Gilberti Kenedy, BALLIVI comitatus de carric had ward of Kylnnahelt (Dunskey).<ref>Exchequer Rolls of Scotland. vol. VI, pp.73\u201374</ref>\n\nGilbert Kennedy of Dunure, bailie of Carrick, did not enjoy Dunskey Castle for long as in AD 1455 Exchequer Rolls of Scotland records that he was compensated for NOT having the ward of Adair.<ref>Exchequer Rolls of Scotland, Vol. VI pp. 73,75</ref> If he was the same Gilbert, he married Christian Adair and her son, apparently Rolland Adair, must have come of age about AD1456. Christian Adair Kennedy was a widow and Dunskey apparently was resigned by Gilbert Kennedy then shown as of Quhiltis which may have been \"White Hills\" next to/or Kilhilt / Kinhilt, to William Earl of Douglas<ref>Exchequer Rolls of Scotland. Vol. VI, p.199</ref> who in turn must have assigned it over to Rolland Adair when he came of age.\n\nIn AD 1457 the Exchequer Rolls, Vigtoun (Wigtownshire) listed \"Libri Responsionum\" notes that Rolandi Adair t. Gilhelt (Kilhelt) had sasine of Crecach, Dunnone, Pennyanach, Kildonan (Dunskey, o'wise Portree see p.&nbsp;688), Carny, and Lochbeg (Laughbeg or Middle Laigh).<ref>Exchequer Rolls of Scotland, vol. IX (appendix) p.666</ref> Carny is shown on Pont's map as \"Karn Multibrugh\" north of Lefnol (Leffnoll / Lesnoll / Lochnoll) and as \"Cairn\" on Ainslie's 1782 map of the County of Wigton, in the National Library of Scotland, digital library early maps<ref name=\"maps\">{{cite web|url=http://maps.nls.uk/counties/view/?id=685#id=685&zoom=3&lat=6615&lon=8661.5&layers=B|publisher=maps.nls.uk|title=View: A map of the county of Wigton. - Counties of Scotland, 1580-1928|accessdate=23 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn AD 1486 ADAIR (Adare), Rolland, deceased, father of William Adair (who must have been under-age) the ward of his lands of Kilhelt, Portre (Dunskey), Kildonane and Drummore, had been granted to an Alexander Bruce c.1468 who had had them in error for 18 years. p.&nbsp;381 error of accounting for 18 years.<ref>Exchequer Rolls of Scotland. Vol. IX, Index p.688 & pp.376\u2013377, p.381</ref>\n\nIn AD 1488 William Adair of Dunskey Castle & Kinhilt and McCulloch of nearby [[Ardwell]], [[Stoneykirk]], were attacked by sheriff Quentin Agnew of [[Lochnaw Castle]] and his band of men. Agnew was pursued before the Lords of Council and in 1489 Agnew had to pay for the goods taken, but was entitled to a rebate if he returned them in good order.<ref>Act. Dom. Cou. 120.  http://www.rps.ac.uk/search.php?action=fc&fn=jamesiv_ms&id=id2751&query=&type=ms&variants=&google= {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20121223070443/http://www.rps.ac.uk/search.php?action=fc&fn=jamesiv_ms&id=id2751&query=&type=ms&variants=&google= |date=23 December 2012 }}</ref>\n\nAbout AD 1489 Dunskey / Dunsky Tower House [ otherwise Castle ] was partially burnt by Sir Alexander (Sandy) M'Culloch of Myrtoun [[Clan McCulloch]].<ref>Registrum Secreti Sigilli (Register of the Privy Seal of Scotland). Vol. I AD1488-1529, printed 1908 Edin. p.45 nos.350\u2013352; p.138 nos.933 & 935</ref> \u2013 3 March 1499, pardon for McCulloch, along with respites for burning the Place of Dunskay granted to Duncane Makke, litil Gilbert Makke, Johne Clerk Makee & Andro Akersane.\n\nIn the early 1500s Dunskey Castle was repaired by the Adairs of Kinhilt (the Hall of Dunskey was rebuilt and was 36feet by 17feet).<ref>Hereditary Sheriffs of Galloway. Vol. I. (pub.1893) p.312. https://archive.org/stream/hereditarysherif01agneuoft#page/312/mode/2up</ref>  The Adairs built the [[Castle of St. John]] in nearby [[Stranraer]] [[Wigtownshire]] about 1510.<ref name=Groome>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scottish-places.info/features/featurehistory4691.html  |author=Groome, Francis H. |work=Ordnance Gazetteer of Scotland: A Survey of Scottish Topography, Statistical, Biographical and Historical |title=Dunskey |accessdate=7 November 2008 |year=1882\u20131885}}</ref>\n\n29 August 1496 \"Anent the complaynt made be Wilzeam Adaire of Kilhelt and Archibald Makculloch of [[Ardwell]] apoun Schir Alexander McCulloch of Mertoune, knicht [[Clan McCulloch]], Owchtre McDowell of Gerthloy (Uchtred McDowell of Garthland) [[Clan Macdowall]], and thare complicis, that quhair thai war dylatit of art and part of the slauchter of umquhile DYONYSE of Hammyltoun, quilkis was slane on Mydsummer evin that last was, in the toune of Wigtoun, thai bean innocent thareof, and was redy al tymes to underly our soverane Lordis lawis tharefore as was allegiit, quharefore the persons forsaid with thare complicis assegit the place of DUNSKAY pertenyng to the sade Wilzeam Adair and rasit fyre and byrnt the sammyn and skaithit the said Wilzeam in househald geire tharethrou, extending to the soume of xl li., throw the quhilk fyre rasing thai birnt ane box pertenyng to Elyse McCulloch quhilk thai had in keping and in it j li. and the skaith of the birnyng of the sade Wilzeam house extending to xx li., and als that thai tuke and spulzeit fra the sade Wilzeam foure horses with a part of barkit hydis, as was rychtsa allegiit, and als fra the sade Archbald McCulloch and his pure folkis insicht gudis of househald to the availe of xxx li., togidder with ix of ky and oxin, xviij of schepe, xvj horses and meris, tane be the sade Schir Alexander and his complicis as was inlikewise allegiit.\"<ref>Acts of the Lords of Council in Civil Causes. vol. II, AD1496-1501, pub. 1918.  p.38</ref>\n\nAfter September 1513 Ninian Adair of Kinhilt, as son and heir of William Adair who was killed at [[Flodden]] with McDowell, had [[Sasine]] (delivery of feudal property) of the estate.<ref>Exchequer Rolls of Scotland. vol. XIV p.526</ref> Four years later Ninian had a renewal of the tack which had been granted to his father in AD1512. It is said that Ninian Adair rebuilt the castle of Dunskey on a more magnificent scale than ever, and to put an end to the feud with the MacDowells he espoused Janet McDowell, a daughter of the house of Garthland [[Garthland Castle]]. The ground floor plan of Dunskey appears to show this new enlarged section (three cellars facing the land-side of Dunskey Castle with the \"new\" hall with a huge fireplace on the next floor).<ref>RCAHMS Aerial view photo DP105874</ref> The arched entrance appeared to be approximately at the south-eastern bottom corner room with circular steps leading up to the new hall. The archway to the entrance can be seen in Francis Grose's drawing, but only the top portion of the archway can now be seen. One peculiar aspect was that one of the new cellars or vaults appeared not to have had a door. Another aspect was  \"...we went by water to see the ruins of an old castle (Dunskey), under this house, in the rock, is a cave, which, they say, goes a considerable distance under ground...\".<ref>Tours in Scotland 1677 and 1681, by Thomas Kirk & Ralph Thoresby.  edit. P. Hume Brown. p.48</ref> This cave may be shown in a photo of Dunskey Castle on Geograph.<ref>Cave under Dunskey Castle. https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/922851</ref>   There are other mentions of a piper \"ghost\" playing and pacing up and down perhaps in the cave.<ref>New Statistical Account of Scotland.  vol. IV, pub.1845. p.132</ref><ref name=\"archive\">{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/newstatisticala12clergoog#page/n1120/mode/1up|publisher=archive.org|title=The new statistical account of Scotland|accessdate=23 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn AD 1520\u20131521 Ninian Adair had only a short time to enjoy his new additions to Dunskey Castle as in AD1523 his son William was mentioned as his heir.<ref>Rotuli Scaccarii Regum Scotorum, vol. XV p.571 AD1523</ref> In 1520\u20131521 (as Ninian Adair's heir, William, was under-age) the warde his lands (including Dunskey castle) were put into the hands of the [[Gilbert Kennedy, 2nd Earl of Cassilis]] and Lord Maxwell.<ref>Registrum Secreti Sigilli Scotorum (8 Jac. V) AD1520-1521 p.485 no.3159 v.148</ref>\n\n==17th century==\n[[Image:Dunskey Castle.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Dunskey Castle from the north-east. photo by Anne Burgess]] [[Image:Dunskey Castle2.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Dunskey Castle. photo by Joe McCartney]]\n\nc.1600 \"in Ninian Adair's time and his sons\" a browney \"hanted\" his house of Dunsky.<ref>Montgomery manuscripts, pub.1830</ref><ref name=\"google2\">{{cite book|title=Inquisitionum ad Capellam domini regis retornatorum, quae in publicis archivis Scotiae adhuc servantur, abbreviatio|date=1840|publisher=House of Commons of Gret Britain|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZlKELERXEj8C&pg=PA1780|page=1780|accessdate=23 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 April 1608 the lands of Guilielmus (William) Adair heir of Niniani Adair de Kinhilt, included 10 lib. terranium de Portrie cum castro de Dunskey in parochie de Inche [[Inch, Wigtownshire]].<ref name=\"google2\"/><ref>Retours of Service of Heirs, Inquisitions Specials \u2013 Wigton. p.33</ref>  William Adair marriage contract 18 April 1580 to Rosina MacClellan of Galston whose brother, Sir Robert McClellan (McLellan) of [[MacLellan's Castle]] Kirkcudbright [[Clan MacLellan]] married 1614 Mary Montgomery, eldest daughter of Sir [[Hugh Montgomery, 1st Viscount Montgomery]] of Ards, county Down, Ireland.<ref>The Scots Peerage. Volume V. p.267 https://archive.org/stream/scotspeeragefoun05paul#page/266/mode/2up</ref>\n\nIn February 1620, \"10 librat of antiqui extentus de Portry\" including \"3 mercatas de Marok cum castro de Doneskey\" was acquired by [[Hugh Montgomery, 1st Viscount Montgomery]] who extended the castle by building the \"Gallery\" leading off from the \"Hall\" and vaults under the \"Gallery\".<ref>Register of the Great Seal of Scotland, vol. VII, p.772, no.2127.  https://archive.org/stream/registrummagnisi07scot#page/772/mode/2up</ref>\n\nOn 24 August 1632 Sara Maxwell, Viscountess Montgomerie, wrote a letter to her husband, [[Hugh Montgomery, 1st Viscount Montgomery]] (Montgomerie of Airds) \"It seameth ye ar causing your workmen goe on both in your building and theikine of your Gallerie att Dunskay. They ar necessarie thingis to be outride, seeing ye have put theme so far agait. Bot I am suire they ar greit chargeis vnto yow quhilk now can noght be helpeit ; bot your lordship most compleit thame, as ye haue done many greater turne.\"<ref>The Montgomery Manuscripts. Vol. I by William Montgomery, ed. Rev. George Hill, pub. AD1869. p.112 Montgomery Letters</ref>\n\nOn 28 July 1646 Visc. Hugh Montgomery (Hugu Vicecomes De Airdis) of Ards, co Down, Ireland, was retoured heir to his father [[Hugh Montgomery, 2nd Viscount Montgomery]], lands listed included castro de Dunskei.<ref name=\"google3\">{{cite book|title=Inquisitionum ad Capellam domini regis retornatorum, quae in publicis archivis Scotiae adhuc servantur, abbreviatio|date=1840|publisher=House of Commons of Gret Britain|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZlKELERXEj8C|accessdate=23 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 June 1653 \"Johne Shaw of Grenocke\" was granted Dunskey by Andrew Wardlaw. The deed was a little unclear. \"Joane Montgrumie alias Mackmath, relict of the \"deceased\" Hew Montgrumie sometime of Balharie in the Country of Doune, (Ireland), gentleman\" \"the 3 merk land of Marrock, with the castle, tower and fortalice of Dunskey situate thereupon\" to which lands had pertained to Hew Montgomery now Viscount of Airds, his father (John Shaw's father-in-law?), and were apprised from him on 1 August 1650 at the instance of Joane Montgrumie alias Mackmath relict of the deceased Hew Montgrumie sometime of Balharie in the country of Doune, Gentleman (Balhenry ? co Down, Ireland), and of Maister Samuell Rutherfuird [[Samuel Rutherford]] professor of divinity in the University of Saint Andrews, now spouse of Joan Montgrumie alias Mackmath, for his interest, for payment of 2,000 pounds Scots.<ref>Register of the Great Seal of Scotland. Under the Commonwealth (Cromwell). Vol. X, pp.81\u201382, no.164</ref>\n\nAD1654 From [[Timothy Pont]]'s map \"Two castles stronger than the rest may be seen in the Rinns, Kennedy on Loch Isle of the Earl of Cassillis, and Scaeodunum (called in the vernacular Dunskey), (Scot dun / castle ? ) founded by the ancestors of Robert Adair on a sheer rock by the sea.\"<ref>National Library of Scotland. Blaeu Atlas of Scotland, Pagination: 50.  Title: Gallovidiae.  http://maps.nls.uk/atlas/blaeu/page.cfm?id=95</ref>\n\nViscount Montgomery was heavily in mortgage after sustaining his troops for a long period, (as was Sir Robert McLellan), so Dunskey Castle passed to the Blair family who were or had been Ministers at Portmontgomery als Portpatrick.<ref name=Groome/>  Register of the Great Seal of Scotland, Vol. IX. AD1634-1651. p.&nbsp;814 #2156 Apud Edinburgh, 10 Jan (1649) REX, \u2013 concessit et de novo dedit (KING Charles I \u2013 consents to a new deed ?) M. JACOBO BLAIR (Rev. James Blair) ministro Verbi Dei apud ecclesiam de Port-Montgomrie (minister of church at Port-Montgomery / Portpatrick Wigtownshire) ejus heredibus, successoribus et assignatis quibuscunque, irredimabiliter, \u2013 4 mercatas terrarum de Meikle Portspittell, 3 mercatas de Litle Portspittell.\n\nOn 19 October 1667 there was a marriage contract between John Blair, (son of the minister of Portpatrick, Wigtownshire, Scotland) and Jean Agnew, dau of Patrick Agnew, Laird of Sheuchan. A witness was George Stewart of Tonderghie and of Barcly, Wigtownshire, (son of Sir Robert Stewart Governor of Culmore, Londonderry, and a descendant of the [[Castle Stewart of Penninghame|Castle Stewart]] of [[Penninghame]] family), who had married Elizabeth, daughter of James Blair of Dunskey Castle. George Stewart's sister, Agnes Stewart married William Houston of Cutreoch, [[Whithorn]], Wigtownshire. Three other witnesses were James & Hew Blair, brothers of above John Blair, and Patrick Kennedy, Provost of [[Stranraer]]. Agnes Blair's (n\u00e9e Agnew) sister m. Alexander Adair, son of Robert Adair whose father, William Adair had previously owned Dunskey Castle. John Blair had acted as agent for Viscount Montgomery of Airds who had owned Dunskey Castle. The Viscount was in financial difficulties due to the upkeep of his troops, and had borrowed largely from his agent who foreclosed on a mortgage and became possessed of the whole of the Montgomery property in Galloway.<ref>The Agnews of Lochnaw p.365</ref>\n\nIn AD 1657 John Blair of Dunskey, valuation 946 pounds 13sh 4p.. Valuations of the Shire of Wigtown, 1667.<ref>Archaeological and Historical Collections Relating to Ayrshire and Galloway. p.102, note 11.  https://archive.org/stream/archologicaland01unkngoog#page/n175/mode/2up</ref>\n\nOn 11 September 1672 There was a ratification to John Blair of Dunskey and his wife Jean Agnew of their lands to be called \"barony of Dunskey\" and by 1684 the Laird of Dunskey and his wife had moved to nearby Killantringan, Portpatrick.<ref>AD1684 Parish Lists for Wigtownshire. Parish Portpatrick. p.53</ref><ref name=\"rps\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rps.ac.uk/search.php?a=fcf&fn=charlesii_trans&id=id18598&t=trans|publisher=rps.ac.uk|title=Records of the Parliaments of Scotland|accessdate=23 February 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"archive2\">{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/parishlistsofwig72scot#page/52/mode/2up|publisher=archive.org|title=Parish lists of Wigtownshire and Minnigaff, 1684|accessdate=23 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nBy 1684 Dunskey Castle was in ruin, only 50 years after Viscount Montgomery had added the new gallery wing extensions.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090607093646/http://guide.visitscotland.com/vs/guide/5,en,SCH1/objectId,SIG58008Svs,curr,GBP,season,at1,selectedEntry,home/home.html Information from Visit Scotland]\n\n{{Castles in Dumfries and Galloway}}\n{{Coord|54.835413|N|5.109874|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Houses completed in the 12th century]]\n[[Category:Castles in Dumfries and Galloway]]\n[[Category:Castles in Wigtownshire]]\n[[Category:Scheduled Ancient Monuments in Dumfries and Galloway]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=February 2017}}\n{{synthesis|date=February 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2017}}\n[[Image:DUNSKEY CASTLE by Francis Grose, 1790.jpg|thumb|right|300px|Dunskey Castle by Francis Grose 1790.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/antiquitiesofsc02gros|title=The antiquities of Scotland|first=Francis|last=Grose|date=16 November 1797|publisher=London : Printed for Hooper & Wigstead ...|via=Internet Archive}}</ref>]]\n'''Dunskey Castle''' is a ruined, 12th century [[tower house]] or castle, located {{convert|0.5|mi|km}} south of the village of [[Portpatrick]], [[Rhinns]], Wigtownshire, on the south-west coast of [[Scotland]].<ref>Royal National Directory of Scotland.(1915) p.1368 https://archive.org/stream/slatersroyalnati1915dire#page/1368/mode/1up</ref>\n\nDunskey Castle is a [[scheduled monument]],<ref>{{Historic Environment Scotland|num=SM2017|desc=Dunskey Castle|access-date=27 March 2019}}</ref> a 'nationally important' [[archaeological site]] or historic building, given protection against unauthorised change.\n\n==Description==\nThe three-storey [[L-plan castle|L-plan]] structure is sited on a promontory, with a rock-cut ditch, {{convert|15|m|ft}} wide by {{convert|2.5|m|ft}} deep, defending the only access, from the north-east.<ref name=LBR>{{Historic Environment Scotland|num=LB16777|desc=Dunskey Castle|cat=A (removed)|access-date=27 March 2019|fewer-links=yes}}</ref> The castle measures {{convert|30|by|14.3|m|ft}}, with walls {{convert|1.5|m|ft}} thick, although the building is now a roofless shell. The north-east wing is of a later date, and the foundations of a south range are visible. Near the castle are the remains of a watchtower, {{convert|7|m|ft}} square, built on the cliff edge.<ref name=CANMORE>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rcahms.gov.uk/pls/portal/newcanmore.newcandig_details_gis?inumlink=60632 |title=Dunskey Castle, NMRS Number: NX05SW 3 |work=[[Canmore (database)|CANMORE]] |publisher=[[RCAHMS]] |accessdate=7 November 2008}}</ref> [[Timothy Pont]]'s map drawn c. 1580 \u2013 1590 shows Dunskay Castle with 2 watchtowers on the cliff edge fronting the sea.<ref>National Library of Scotland http://maps.nls.uk/atlas/blaeu/page.cfm?id=95</ref>  [[Francis Grose]]'s drawing dated show of 10 May 1790s the ruins of the foundations and sea-wall on the south and what looks to be the large entrance door in the southern corner from where the inside staircase may have led straight up to the new \"Hall\" built c.1520. Grose's drawing shows Ireland (approx. Island Magee / Larne area) in the background across the sea.<ref>\"The Antiquities of Scotland, volume 2, pp.191\u2013192, by Francis Grose, pub. 1791 by Hooper.  https://books.google.com/books?id=Ai0DAAAAYAAJ&q=Dunskey#v=snippet&q=Dunskey&f=false</ref>\n\nIn virtue of a tradition preserved in the [[Book of Leinster]], W. J. Watson identifies the place named in it as Port Rig (Portrie, Portree) with the later [[Portpatrick]], connecting 'Rig' with Reregonium, which he regards as the royal town of the Novantae and places in this region. He would thus carry [[Portpatrick]]'s history back to the first century of our era, while he dates a rather later reference to about AD 250.<ref>History of the Celtic Placenames of Scotland. {{cite web |url=http://www.spns.org.uk/watsdg.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-05-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140821230319/http://www.spns.org.uk/watsdg.html |archivedate=21 August 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Portpatrick was known as the port of Castle Dunskey.\n\nDunskey is undoubtedly romantic. It was a location for the 1951 film \"Kidnapped\" of Robert Louis Stevenson's novel, as well as for the 1952 film ''[[Hunted (film)|Hunted]]''.\n\nThe owner, Lady Amy McFall, restricts public access to the castle.\n\n==13th and 14th centuries==\nIn the 1290s, [[John Comyn, Earl of Buchan]], had a licence from [[Edward I of England]], reigned 1272\u20131307) to dig for lead in the Calf of Man (off the coast of the Isle of Man), to cover eight towers of the [[Cruggleton Castle]] / Crogiltoun Castle in Wigtownshire. Was Dunskey Castle built about this time ?<ref>Chalmer's Caledonia (vol. iii. p. 372), quoted by Cumming (History of the Isle of Man, p. 307)</ref> and in AD1291 the nearby [[Wigtown Castle]] was in the hands of the same Edward I who committed it to the charge of Walter de Currie or Cory / Corry / Coree (laird of Dunskey). King Edward I ultimately conferred [[Wigtown Castle]] (and Dunskey Castle ?) on [[John Balliol]] the Scottish King (reigned AD1292-1296 after which Scotland was without a monarch for 10 years and Sir William Wallace fought the English in 1297, but was defeated at Falkirk in 1298).<ref>The Edinburgh Encyclopedia, vol.18, p.521, by Sir David Brewster, published 1832 in Philadelphia by Joseph Parker.  https://books.google.com/books?id=O4wEAAAAYAAJ&q=Wigton#v=snippet&q=Wigton&f=false</ref>\n\nBy 10 October 1303 Walter de Corry was dead and his lands were taken into the King's hands (King Edward I of England).<ref>Fine Rolls, i 483</ref><ref>Dumfriesshire and Galloway \"Transactions and Journal of Proceedings\" Ed: R.C. Reid, pub.1916. Third Series, Vol. IV, p.30 Early History of the Corries</ref><ref>external link :  [http://www.dgnhas.org.uk/transonline/SerIII-Vol4.pdf] http://www.medievalgenealogy.org.uk/sources/rolls.shtml</ref><ref>Calendar of the Fine Rolls. Vol. I. Edward I. AD.1272\u20131307, p.483 (493 of 798 on external link, Brigham Young University Library copy</ref>\n\nOn 28 August 1296 the [[Ragman Rolls]] for Wigtownshire had been compiled at Berwick-on-Tweed, which time and place King Edward I of England also convened a Parliament of those\nScottish nobles summoned by him to attend at the border city. The Wigtownshire roll contained 26 names, and some who were later associated with Dunskey Castle were Thomas de KITHEHILT (Adair of Kinhilt / Kilhelt) ; Fergus MakDowylt (MacDowell) ; Thomas MacUlagh (MacCullough / McCullagh) ; Andrew (McDowell) de Logan ; Dougal MacDowly (MacDowell / McDowell) ; Gilbert de Hanneth (Hannay) ; William MacUlagh (MacCullough / McCullagh) ; Michel MacUlagh (MacCullough) ; Johan Seneschal (Stewart, from whom descended the Earls of Darnly and Lennox) ; [[Maria de Ergadia|Maria, Queen of Mann and the Isles]].<ref>Publication of The Bannatyne Club. page 145 (178 of 274).  https://www.scribd.com/doc/92560287/Ragman-Roll-Instrument-a-Public-a-00-Tho-Mu-Oft</ref>\n\nc. AD1326  \"Index of Charters, &c. by King Robert I.\" King Robert I  [[Robert the Bruce]] (born 1274 reigned AD1306-1329 after the Interregnum AD1296-1306). p.&nbsp;27 \"In the Roll of Robert the First, marked on the back with this mark, X.  1. Carta to Thomas Edzear (probably Adair) of the lands of Kildonan, in the Rynes, Wigtoun\".<ref>An Index, drawn up about the year 1629 of many Records of Charters, granted between the years 1309 and 1413, by William Robertson, Esq. Edinburgh. p.27.  https://archive.org/details/indexdrawnupabou00grea</ref>\n\nAnother version of Adair / Odeir / Edzear of Dunskey Castle in Portry / Portrie / Port-N-Rye, is :  c. AD1326  \"Index A.  From old vol. XXII Fol. 25 verso \u2013 Ane Littill small skine quahirin ar conteinet certane complaintis of deforcementis and of haldingis of landis quhilkis ar decydit be the parliament. Carta Thomas Odeir de terris de Kildonan Dromin Porthie\" [ Portrie = Dunsky & Kinhilt ].<ref>Register of the Great Seal of Scotland. vol.1 AD1306-1424 p.555, Appendix 2. no.681</ref> c.1600 Kildonan Castle appeared to be a large castle just east of Dunskey Castle, shown on [[Timothy Pont]]'s map in Blaeu's Atlas.<ref>National Library Scotland, Blaeu Atlas. http://maps.nls.uk/atlas/blaeu/page.cfm?id=95</ref>\n\n==15th & 16th centuries==\nOn 10 November 1426 Nigello Adare de Portar (Portrie \u2013 Dunskey) was a witness to the restoration of the lands of Lochnaw [[Lochnaw Castle]], by Willelmi de Douglas, dom. de [[Leswalt]] to Andree Agnew.<ref>Registrum magni sigilli regum Scotorum, Vol. II. AD1424-1513, page 40, no.183. https://archive.org/stream/registrummagnisi02scot#page/40/mode/2up</ref>  This Nigello Adare may have died prior AD1456.\n\nIn AD 1456 [[Gilbert Kennedy, 1st Lord Kennedy]] of Dunure obtained the ward of Kynhilt (with Dunskey Castle) as shown in Exchequer Rolls of Scotland, Kennedy \u2013 Gilbert of DUNURE \"OBTAINS ward of Kynhilt\" (Dunskey) see 208 & 347.<ref>Exchequer Rolls of Scotland, vol. VI index p.730</ref> It is interesting that R.M.S. vol. II index on p.&nbsp;1134 BALLIVUS de Carrick, lists p.&nbsp;94 no.414, 13 February 1450 Gilbert Kennedy of Dunure \"REX confirmavit Gilberto Kenedy de Dunure consang. suo, \u2013 quod ipse Gilbertus et heredes sui masculi essent caput totius progeniei sue tam in calumpniis quam in aliis articulis et negotiis ad KENKYNOLL pertinere valentibus; unaetum officio ballivi comitatus de Carric et hominum ipsius dectione et cum armorum ostensione in omnibus, sub comite de Carric qui pro tempore fuerit ; \u2013 que idem Gilb. personaliter resignavit.\" iv. 182.<ref>Register of the Great Seal of Scotland. vol. II, index on p.1134</ref> \u2013 was he a bailie & Kenkynol, as Exchequer Roll AD1455 shows Gilberti Kenedy, BALLIVI comitatus de carric had ward of Kylnnahelt (Dunskey).<ref>Exchequer Rolls of Scotland. vol. VI, pp.73\u201374</ref>\n\nGilbert Kennedy of Dunure, bailie of Carrick, did not enjoy Dunskey Castle for long as in AD 1455 Exchequer Rolls of Scotland records that he was compensated for NOT having the ward of Adair.<ref>Exchequer Rolls of Scotland, Vol. VI pp. 73,75</ref> If he was the same Gilbert, he married Christian Adair and her son, apparently Rolland Adair, must have come of age about AD1456. Christian Adair Kennedy was a widow and Dunskey apparently was resigned by Gilbert Kennedy then shown as of Quhiltis which may have been \"White Hills\" next to/or Kilhilt / Kinhilt, to William Earl of Douglas<ref>Exchequer Rolls of Scotland. Vol. VI, p.199</ref> who in turn must have assigned it over to Rolland Adair when he came of age.\n\nIn AD 1457 the Exchequer Rolls, Vigtoun (Wigtownshire) listed \"Libri Responsionum\" notes that Rolandi Adair t. Gilhelt (Kilhelt) had sasine of Crecach, Dunnone, Pennyanach, Kildonan (Dunskey, o'wise Portree see p.&nbsp;688), Carny, and Lochbeg (Laughbeg or Middle Laigh).<ref>Exchequer Rolls of Scotland, vol. IX (appendix) p.666</ref> Carny is shown on Pont's map as \"Karn Multibrugh\" north of Lefnol (Leffnoll / Lesnoll / Lochnoll) and as \"Cairn\" on Ainslie's 1782 map of the County of Wigton, in the National Library of Scotland, digital library early maps<ref name=\"maps\">{{cite web|url=http://maps.nls.uk/counties/view/?id=685#id=685&zoom=3&lat=6615&lon=8661.5&layers=B|publisher=maps.nls.uk|title=View: A map of the county of Wigton. - Counties of Scotland, 1580-1928|accessdate=23 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn AD 1486 ADAIR (Adare), Rolland, deceased, father of William Adair (who must have been under-age) the ward of his lands of Kilhelt, Portre (Dunskey), Kildonane and Drummore, had been granted to an Alexander Bruce c.1468 who had had them in error for 18 years. p.&nbsp;381 error of accounting for 18 years.<ref>Exchequer Rolls of Scotland. Vol. IX, Index p.688 & pp.376\u2013377, p.381</ref>\n\nIn AD 1488 William Adair of Dunskey Castle & Kinhilt and McCulloch of nearby [[Ardwell]], [[Stoneykirk]], were attacked by sheriff Quentin Agnew of [[Lochnaw Castle]] and his band of men. Agnew was pursued before the Lords of Council and in 1489 Agnew had to pay for the goods taken, but was entitled to a rebate if he returned them in good order.<ref>Act. Dom. Cou. 120.  http://www.rps.ac.uk/search.php?action=fc&fn=jamesiv_ms&id=id2751&query=&type=ms&variants=&google= {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20121223070443/http://www.rps.ac.uk/search.php?action=fc&fn=jamesiv_ms&id=id2751&query=&type=ms&variants=&google= |date=23 December 2012 }}</ref>\n\nAbout AD 1489 Dunskey / Dunsky Tower House [ otherwise Castle ] was partially burnt by Sir Alexander (Sandy) M'Culloch of Myrtoun [[Clan McCulloch]].<ref>Registrum Secreti Sigilli (Register of the Privy Seal of Scotland). Vol. I AD1488-1529, printed 1908 Edin. p.45 nos.350\u2013352; p.138 nos.933 & 935</ref> \u2013 3 March 1499, pardon for McCulloch, along with respites for burning the Place of Dunskay granted to Duncane Makke, litil Gilbert Makke, Johne Clerk Makee & Andro Akersane.\n\nIn the early 1500s Dunskey Castle was repaired by the Adairs of Kinhilt (the Hall of Dunskey was rebuilt and was 36feet by 17feet).<ref>Hereditary Sheriffs of Galloway. Vol. I. (pub.1893) p.312. https://archive.org/stream/hereditarysherif01agneuoft#page/312/mode/2up</ref>  The Adairs built the [[Castle of St. John]] in nearby [[Stranraer]] [[Wigtownshire]] about 1510.<ref name=Groome>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scottish-places.info/features/featurehistory4691.html  |author=Groome, Francis H. |work=Ordnance Gazetteer of Scotland: A Survey of Scottish Topography, Statistical, Biographical and Historical |title=Dunskey |accessdate=7 November 2008 |year=1882\u20131885}}</ref>\n\n29 August 1496 \"Anent the complaynt made be Wilzeam Adaire of Kilhelt and Archibald Makculloch of [[Ardwell]] apoun Schir Alexander McCulloch of Mertoune, knicht [[Clan McCulloch]], Owchtre McDowell of Gerthloy (Uchtred McDowell of Garthland) [[Clan Macdowall]], and thare complicis, that quhair thai war dylatit of art and part of the slauchter of umquhile DYONYSE of Hammyltoun, quilkis was slane on Mydsummer evin that last was, in the toune of Wigtoun, thai bean innocent thareof, and was redy al tymes to underly our soverane Lordis lawis tharefore as was allegiit, quharefore the persons forsaid with thare complicis assegit the place of DUNSKAY pertenyng to the sade Wilzeam Adair and rasit fyre and byrnt the sammyn and skaithit the said Wilzeam in househald geire tharethrou, extending to the soume of xl li., throw the quhilk fyre rasing thai birnt ane box pertenyng to Elyse McCulloch quhilk thai had in keping and in it j li. and the skaith of the birnyng of the sade Wilzeam house extending to xx li., and als that thai tuke and spulzeit fra the sade Wilzeam foure horses with a part of barkit hydis, as was rychtsa allegiit, and als fra the sade Archbald McCulloch and his pure folkis insicht gudis of househald to the availe of xxx li., togidder with ix of ky and oxin, xviij of schepe, xvj horses and meris, tane be the sade Schir Alexander and his complicis as was inlikewise allegiit.\"<ref>Acts of the Lords of Council in Civil Causes. vol. II, AD1496-1501, pub. 1918.  p.38</ref>\n\nAfter September 1513 Ninian Adair of Kinhilt, as son and heir of William Adair who was killed at [[Flodden]] with McDowell, had [[Sasine]] (delivery of feudal property) of the estate.<ref>Exchequer Rolls of Scotland. vol. XIV p.526</ref> Four years later Ninian had a renewal of the tack which had been granted to his father in AD1512. It is said that Ninian Adair rebuilt the castle of Dunskey on a more magnificent scale than ever, and to put an end to the feud with the MacDowells he espoused Janet McDowell, a daughter of the house of Garthland [[Garthland Castle]]. The ground floor plan of Dunskey appears to show this new enlarged section (three cellars facing the land-side of Dunskey Castle with the \"new\" hall with a huge fireplace on the next floor).<ref>RCAHMS Aerial view photo DP105874</ref> The arched entrance appeared to be approximately at the south-eastern bottom corner room with circular steps leading up to the new hall. The archway to the entrance can be seen in Francis Grose's drawing, but only the top portion of the archway can now be seen. One peculiar aspect was that one of the new cellars or vaults appeared not to have had a door. Another aspect was  \"...we went by water to see the ruins of an old castle (Dunskey), under this house, in the rock, is a cave, which, they say, goes a considerable distance under ground...\".<ref>Tours in Scotland 1677 and 1681, by Thomas Kirk & Ralph Thoresby.  edit. P. Hume Brown. p.48</ref> This cave may be shown in a photo of Dunskey Castle on Geograph.<ref>Cave under Dunskey Castle. https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/922851</ref>   There are other mentions of a piper \"ghost\" playing and pacing up and down perhaps in the cave.<ref>New Statistical Account of Scotland.  vol. IV, pub.1845. p.132</ref><ref name=\"archive\">{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/newstatisticala12clergoog#page/n1120/mode/1up|publisher=archive.org|title=The new statistical account of Scotland|accessdate=23 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn AD 1520\u20131521 Ninian Adair had only a short time to enjoy his new additions to Dunskey Castle as in AD1523 his son William was mentioned as his heir.<ref>Rotuli Scaccarii Regum Scotorum, vol. XV p.571 AD1523</ref> In 1520\u20131521 (as Ninian Adair's heir, William, was under-age) the warde his lands (including Dunskey castle) were put into the hands of the [[Gilbert Kennedy, 2nd Earl of Cassilis]] and Lord Maxwell.<ref>Registrum Secreti Sigilli Scotorum (8 Jac. V) AD1520-1521 p.485 no.3159 v.148</ref>\n\n==17th century==\n[[Image:Dunskey Castle.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Dunskey Castle from the north-east. photo by Anne Burgess]] [[Image:Dunskey Castle2.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Dunskey Castle. photo by Joe McCartney]]\n\nc.1600 \"in Ninian Adair's time and his sons\" a browney \"hanted\" his house of Dunsky.<ref>Montgomery manuscripts, pub.1830</ref><ref name=\"google2\">{{cite book|title=Inquisitionum ad Capellam domini regis retornatorum, quae in publicis archivis Scotiae adhuc servantur, abbreviatio|date=1840|publisher=House of Commons of Gret Britain|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZlKELERXEj8C&pg=PA1780|page=1780|accessdate=23 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 April 1608 the lands of Guilielmus (William) Adair heir of Niniani Adair de Kinhilt, included 10 lib. terranium de Portrie cum castro de Dunskey in parochie de Inche [[Inch, Wigtownshire]].<ref name=\"google2\"/><ref>Retours of Service of Heirs, Inquisitions Specials \u2013 Wigton. p.33</ref>  William Adair marriage contract 18 April 1580 to Rosina MacClellan of Galston whose brother, Sir Robert McClellan (McLellan) of [[MacLellan's Castle]] Kirkcudbright [[Clan MacLellan]] married 1614 Mary Montgomery, eldest daughter of Sir [[Hugh Montgomery, 1st Viscount Montgomery]] of Ards, county Down, Ireland.<ref>The Scots Peerage. Volume V. p.267 https://archive.org/stream/scotspeeragefoun05paul#page/266/mode/2up</ref>\n\nIn February 1620, \"10 librat of antiqui extentus de Portry\" including \"3 mercatas de Marok cum castro de Doneskey\" was acquired by [[Hugh Montgomery, 1st Viscount Montgomery]] who extended the castle by building the \"Gallery\" leading off from the \"Hall\" and vaults under the \"Gallery\".<ref>Register of the Great Seal of Scotland, vol. VII, p.772, no.2127.  https://archive.org/stream/registrummagnisi07scot#page/772/mode/2up</ref>\n\nOn 24 August 1632 Sara Maxwell, Viscountess Montgomerie, wrote a letter to her husband, [[Hugh Montgomery, 1st Viscount Montgomery]] (Montgomerie of Airds) \"It seameth ye ar causing your workmen goe on both in your building and theikine of your Gallerie att Dunskay. They ar necessarie thingis to be outride, seeing ye have put theme so far agait. Bot I am suire they ar greit chargeis vnto yow quhilk now can noght be helpeit ; bot your lordship most compleit thame, as ye haue done many greater turne.\"<ref>The Montgomery Manuscripts. Vol. I by William Montgomery, ed. Rev. George Hill, pub. AD1869. p.112 Montgomery Letters</ref>\n\nOn 28 July 1646 Visc. Hugh Montgomery (Hugu Vicecomes De Airdis) of Ards, co Down, Ireland, was retoured heir to his father [[Hugh Montgomery, 2nd Viscount Montgomery]], lands listed included castro de Dunskei.<ref name=\"google3\">{{cite book|title=Inquisitionum ad Capellam domini regis retornatorum, quae in publicis archivis Scotiae adhuc servantur, abbreviatio|date=1840|publisher=House of Commons of Gret Britain|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZlKELERXEj8C|accessdate=23 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 June 1653 \"Johne Shaw of Grenocke\" was granted Dunskey by Andrew Wardlaw. The deed was a little unclear. \"Joane Montgrumie alias Mackmath, relict of the \"deceased\" Hew Montgrumie sometime of Balharie in the Country of Doune, (Ireland), gentleman\" \"the 3 merk land of Marrock, with the castle, tower and fortalice of Dunskey situate thereupon\" to which lands had pertained to Hew Montgomery now Viscount of Airds, his father (John Shaw's father-in-law?), and were apprised from him on 1 August 1650 at the instance of Joane Montgrumie alias Mackmath relict of the deceased Hew Montgrumie sometime of Balharie in the country of Doune, Gentleman (Balhenry ? co Down, Ireland), and of Maister Samuell Rutherfuird [[Samuel Rutherford]] professor of divinity in the University of Saint Andrews, now spouse of Joan Montgrumie alias Mackmath, for his interest, for payment of 2,000 pounds Scots.<ref>Register of the Great Seal of Scotland. Under the Commonwealth (Cromwell). Vol. X, pp.81\u201382, no.164</ref>\n\nAD1654 From [[Timothy Pont]]'s map \"Two castles stronger than the rest may be seen in the Rinns, Kennedy on Loch Isle of the Earl of Cassillis, and Scaeodunum (called in the vernacular Dunskey), (Scot dun / castle ? ) founded by the ancestors of Robert Adair on a sheer rock by the sea.\"<ref>National Library of Scotland. Blaeu Atlas of Scotland, Pagination: 50.  Title: Gallovidiae.  http://maps.nls.uk/atlas/blaeu/page.cfm?id=95</ref>\n\nViscount Montgomery was heavily in mortgage after sustaining his troops for a long period, (as was Sir Robert McLellan), so Dunskey Castle passed to the Blair family who were or had been Ministers at Portmontgomery als Portpatrick.<ref name=Groome/>  Register of the Great Seal of Scotland, Vol. IX. AD1634-1651. p.&nbsp;814 #2156 Apud Edinburgh, 10 Jan (1649) REX, \u2013 concessit et de novo dedit (KING Charles I \u2013 consents to a new deed ?) M. JACOBO BLAIR (Rev. James Blair) ministro Verbi Dei apud ecclesiam de Port-Montgomrie (minister of church at Port-Montgomery / Portpatrick Wigtownshire) ejus heredibus, successoribus et assignatis quibuscunque, irredimabiliter, \u2013 4 mercatas terrarum de Meikle Portspittell, 3 mercatas de Litle Portspittell.\n\nOn 19 October 1667 there was a marriage contract between John Blair, (son of the minister of Portpatrick, Wigtownshire, Scotland) and Jean Agnew, dau of Patrick Agnew, Laird of Sheuchan. A witness was George Stewart of Tonderghie and of Barcly, Wigtownshire, (son of Sir Robert Stewart Governor of Culmore, Londonderry, and a descendant of the [[Castle Stewart of Penninghame|Castle Stewart]] of [[Penninghame]] family), who had married Elizabeth, daughter of James Blair of Dunskey Castle. George Stewart's sister, Agnes Stewart married William Houston of Cutreoch, [[Whithorn]], Wigtownshire. Three other witnesses were James & Hew Blair, brothers of above John Blair, and Patrick Kennedy, Provost of [[Stranraer]]. Agnes Blair's (n\u00e9e Agnew) sister m. Alexander Adair, son of Robert Adair whose father, William Adair had previously owned Dunskey Castle. John Blair had acted as agent for Viscount Montgomery of Airds who had owned Dunskey Castle. The Viscount was in financial difficulties due to the upkeep of his troops, and had borrowed largely from his agent who foreclosed on a mortgage and became possessed of the whole of the Montgomery property in Galloway.<ref>The Agnews of Lochnaw p.365</ref>\n\nIn AD 1657 John Blair of Dunskey, valuation 946 pounds 13sh 4p.. Valuations of the Shire of Wigtown, 1667.<ref>Archaeological and Historical Collections Relating to Ayrshire and Galloway. p.102, note 11.  https://archive.org/stream/archologicaland01unkngoog#page/n175/mode/2up</ref>\n\nOn 11 September 1672 There was a ratification to John Blair of Dunskey and his wife Jean Agnew of their lands to be called \"barony of Dunskey\" and by 1684 the Laird of Dunskey and his wife had moved to nearby Killantringan, Portpatrick.<ref>AD1684 Parish Lists for Wigtownshire. Parish Portpatrick. p.53</ref><ref name=\"rps\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rps.ac.uk/search.php?a=fcf&fn=charlesii_trans&id=id18598&t=trans|publisher=rps.ac.uk|title=Records of the Parliaments of Scotland|accessdate=23 February 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"archive2\">{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/parishlistsofwig72scot#page/52/mode/2up|publisher=archive.org|title=Parish lists of Wigtownshire and Minnigaff, 1684|accessdate=23 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nBy 1684 Dunskey Castle was in ruin, only 50 years after Viscount Montgomery had added the new gallery wing extensions.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|33em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090607093646/http://guide.visitscotland.com/vs/guide/5,en,SCH1/objectId,SIG58008Svs,curr,GBP,season,at1,selectedEntry,home/home.html Information from Visit Scotland]\n\n{{Castles in Dumfries and Galloway}}\n{{Coord|54.835413|N|5.109874|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Houses completed in the 12th century]]\n[[Category:Castles in Dumfries and Galloway]]\n[[Category:Castles in Wigtownshire]]\n[[Category:Scheduled Ancient Monuments in Dumfries and Galloway]]\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e15th & 16th centuries:add link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dunskey_Castle"}
{"title_page": "Ipoh", "text_new": "{{for|the federal constituency formerly represented in the Dewan Rakyat|Ipoh (federal constituency)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{More citations needed|date=October 2011}}\n{{Advert|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Ipoh\n| settlement_type                 = [[List of cities in Malaysia|City]] and [[List of capitals in Malaysia|state capital]]\n| official_name                   = City of Ipoh<br>{{nobold|''Bandaraya Ipoh''}}\n| translit_lang1                  = Other\n| image_skyline                   = Ipoh composite.jpg\n| image_caption                   = Clockwise from top: Jalan Tun Sambanthan within the Old Town, [[Ipoh railway station|Railway Station]], City Hall, [[St. Michael's Institution]], Perak Tong Temple\n| image_flag                      = Flag of Ipoh, Perak.svg\n| flag_size                       = 115px\n| image_seal                      = Ipoh Emblem.svg\n| nickname                        = City of Millionaires, Bougainvillea City, Silver Valley\n| motto                           = Ipoh Bersih, Hijau dan Maju<br>\n({{lang-en|Ipoh Clean, Green and Progressive}})\n| image_map                       = {{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|type=shape|stroke-width=2|stroke-color=#000000|zoom=10|frame-lat=4.59722222222222|frame-long=101.075}}\n| map_caption                     = Location of Ipoh in Perak\n| pushpin_map                     = #Malaysia#Asia#Earth\n| pushpin_mapsize                 = 275px\n| pushpin_map_caption             = {{Legend inline|#800000|outline=black}} '''Ipoh''' in {{Legend inline|#FEFEEF|outline=black}} '''[[Malaysia]]'''\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|04|35|50|N|101|04|30|E|region:MY|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{flag|Malaysia}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[States of Malaysia|State]]\n| subdivision_type2               = \n| subdivision_name1               = {{flag|Perak}}\n| established_title1              = Establishment\n| established_date1               = Around 1880\n| established_title2              = Granted States Capital status\n| established_date2               = 31 May 1937\n| established_title3              = Granted Municipality status\n| established_date3               = 31 May 1962\n| established_title4              = Granted City status\n| established_date4               = 27 May 1988\n| leader_title                    = Mayor\n| leader_name                     = Rumaizi Baharin\n| area_total_km2                  = 643\n| area_total_sq_mi                = <!-- Leave blank. Value will be auto-converted. -->\n| elevation_m                     = 21.95\n| elevation_ft                    = 72\n| population_total                = 657,892\n| population_as_of                = 2010\n| population_density_km2          = 1023\n| population_density_sq_mi        = <!-- Leave blank. Value will be auto-converted. -->\n| population_metro                = 737,861<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statistics.gov.my/portal/download_Population/files/BPD/ad_2010.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-03-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120521201742/http://www.statistics.gov.my/portal/download_Population/files/BPD/ad_2010.pdf |archivedate=21 May 2012 }}</ref>\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal codes in Malaysia|Postcode]]\n| postal_code                     = 30xxx, 31xxx\n| area_code                       = 05\n| area_code_type                  = \n| iso_code                        = \n| website                         = {{URL|mbi.gov.my}}\n| unemployment_rate               = \n| translit_lang1_type1            = [[Jawi alphabet|Jawi]]\n| translit_lang1_info1            = \u0625\u06a4\u0648\u0647\n| translit_lang1_type2            = [[Chinese language|Chinese]]\n| translit_lang1_info2            = \u6021\u4fdd\n| translit_lang1_type3            = [[Tamil language|Tamil]]\n| translit_lang1_info3            = \u0b88\u0baa\u0bcd\u0baa\u0bcb\n| timezone                        = [[Malaysian Standard Time|MST]]\n| utc_offset                      = +8\n| timezone_DST                    = Not observed\n}}\n\n'''Ipoh''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|i\u02d0|p|o\u028a}}) is the capital city of the [[Malaysia]]n [[States and federal territories of Malaysia|state]] of [[Perak]]. Located by the [[Kinta River]], it is nearly {{Convert|180|km|abbr=on}} north of [[Kuala Lumpur]] and {{Convert|123|km|abbr=on}} southeast of [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] in neighbouring [[Penang]]. {{As of|2010}}, Ipoh contained a population of 657,892, making it the [[List of cities in Malaysia by population|third largest city in Malaysia by population]].<ref name=\"st1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.statistics.gov.my/portal/download_Population/files/population/03ringkasan_kawasan_PBT_Jadual1.pdf|title=Population Distribution by Local Authority Areas and Mukims, 2010 (page 1 & 8)|publisher=Department of Statistics, Malaysia|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150205090002/http://www.statistics.gov.my/portal/download_Population/files/population/03ringkasan_kawasan_PBT_Jadual1.pdf|archivedate=5 February 2015|url-status=dead|accessdate=19 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nOriginally a village, Ipoh began to grow rapidly in the 1880s after huge deposits of [[tin]] were discovered within its vicinity.<ref name=\":0\" /> By 1895, it was the second largest town within the [[Federated Malay States]], which also consisted of [[Selangor]], [[Negeri Sembilan]] and [[Pahang]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.mbi.gov.my/ms/pelawat/info-ipoh/page/0/1|title=Info Ipoh: Halaman 2 dari 2 {{!}} Portal Rasmi Majlis Bandaraya Ipoh (MBI)|website=mbi.gov.my|access-date=2017-08-21}}</ref> Ipoh was declared a city in 1988.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> However, following the depletion of its tin deposits and the collapse of tin prices in the 1970s, the city suffered decades of decline and neglect.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/travel/malaysia/2012/01/09/ipoh/|title=Ipoh - Malaysia {{!}} The Star Online|last=Tam|first=Susan|access-date=2017-08-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.theborneopost.com/2015/02/22/the-city-that-tin-built/|title=The city that tin built|last=Tan|first=Peter|date=2015-02-21|website=BorneoPost Online {{!}} Borneo, Malaysia, Sarawak Daily News|access-date=2017-08-21}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/sleepy-ipoh-awakens|title=Sleepy Ipoh awakens|last=hermes|date=2016-03-22|work=The Straits Times|access-date=2017-08-21|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theedgeproperty.com.my/content/old-town-restored-rightful-place-history-ipoh|title=Old Town restored to rightful place in history of Ipoh|website=theedgeproperty.com.my|language=en|access-date=2017-08-21}}</ref>\n\nIn recent years, Ipoh's popularity as a tourist destination has been significantly boosted by efforts to conserve its [[British Empire|British]] colonial-era architecture.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> The city is also well known for its [[Ipoh cuisine|cuisine]] and natural attractions, such as its limestone hills and caves within which Buddhist temples were built.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ipohecho.com.my/v4/article/2015/05/16/caves-of-the-kinta-valley|title=Ipoh Echo {{!}} Caves of the Kinta Valley|last=net|first=powered by iosc dot|website=IpohEcho.com.my|language=en|access-date=2017-08-21}}</ref> In addition, Ipoh has managed to maintain its reputation as one of the cleanest cities in Malaysia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2017/08/14/ipoh-is-malaysias-cleanest-city/|title=Ipoh is Malaysia's cleanest city - Nation {{!}} The Star Online|website=thestar.com.my|access-date=2017-08-21}}</ref>\n\nIpoh's location between [[Kuala Lumpur]] and [[George Town, Penang|George Town]] has made it a major land transportation hub within [[Peninsular Malaysia|West Malaysia]], with both the [[Keretapi Tanah Melayu|Malayan Railway]]'s [[KTM West Coast Railway Line|West Coast Line]] and the [[North\u2013South Expressway (Malaysia)|North-South Expressway]] cutting through the city. Aside from the land transportation links, Ipoh is also served by the [[Sultan Azlan Shah Airport]].\n\nIpoh is known as the Hipster Capital of Malaysia by various tourism rating and official agencies.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.malaymail.com/s/1160937/ipohs-hipster-town-image-reason-for-new-found-fame-mb-says|title=Malay Mail - Ipoh Hipster Town Image|last=|first=|date=|work=The Malay Mail|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://says.com/my/news/ipoh-listed-in-lonely-planet-best-in-asia-2016|title=SAYS|last=|first=|date=|work=SAYS DOT COM|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/03/03/from-sleepy-city-to-international-draw-new-york-times-hails-ipoh-as-hip-and-mustvisit-holiday-destin/|title=The Star Malaysia|last=|first=|date=|work=The Star Malaysia|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timetravelturtle.com/hipster-ipoh-malaysia/|title=Time Travel Turtle|last=|first=|date=|website=Time Travel Turtle|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nIpoh grew out from the Malay village of Paloh along the banks of the Kinta River in the 1880s.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://db.ipohworld.org/photo/pdf/3875_wzhem140612.pdf|title=The History of Ipoh|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}</ref> Its geographic location in the rich tin-bearing valley of the [[Kinta River]] made it a natural centre of growth.\n\nThe Great Fire of Ipoh in 1892 destroyed over half the town, but also presented an opportunity to rebuild the town in a more orderly grid pattern. Ipoh was subsequently rebuilt in time for the second tin rush and grew rapidly as a result of the booming tin mining industry, particularly in the 1920s and 1930s.\n\nA local [[Hakka people|Hakka]] miner, millionaire Yau Tet Shin, started developing a large tract of the town in the early 1930s, today known as the 'New Town', from the eastern bank of the [[Kinta River]] to Greentown.<ref name=\"ipohworld762\">[http://www.ipohworld.org/blog/?p=762 Ipohworld\u2019s World \u00bb Yau Tet Shin\u2019s New Town Under Construction 1908]. Ipohworld.org. Retrieved 27 September 2013.</ref> In 1937, Ipoh was made the capital of Perak, replacing [[Taiping, Perak|Taiping]].\n\nIpoh was invaded by the Japanese on 15 December 1941. In March 1942, the Japanese Civil Administration or Perak Shu Seicho was set up at the [[St. Michael's Institution]]. After the liberation of Malaya by British forces, Ipoh remained the capital of Perak to this day.<ref>Khoo Salma Nasution & Abdur-Razzaq Lubis, ''Kinta Valley: Pioneering Malaysia's Modern Development'', Ipoh: Perak Academy, 2005. pp. 273\u2013292</ref>\n\nThe decline of the tin mining industry during the latter half of the 20th century caused the growth of Ipoh to stagnate.{{citation needed|date=May 2017}} With the closure of the tin mines, its urban population was forced to seek employment in other cities within Malaysia. In spite of this, Ipoh remains one of the largest cities in Malaysia in terms of population, with tourism now a main driver of the city's economy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.world-guides.com/asia/malaysia/perak/ipoh/ipoh_history.html|title=Ipoh History Facts and Timeline: Ipoh, Perak, Malaysia|website=world-guides.com|language=en|access-date=2017-02-02}}</ref>\n\nIpoh gained Municipal status in 1962, and in 1988, was declared a city by the then [[Sultan of Perak]], [[Azlan Shah of Perak|Sultan Azlan Shah]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Geography ==\n{{Location map many|Malaysia Perak Ipoh|width=300|float=left\n|caption=Locations of Ipoh and its suburbs\n|lat1=4.597222|long1=101.075|label1_size=75 |label1='''Ipoh'''|position1=left\n|lat2=4.720754|long2=101.1212|label2_size=65 |label2=[[Chemor]]|position2=left|mark2=Cyan pog.svg\n|lat3=4.61831|long3=101.140884|label3_size=65 |label3=[[Tambun]]|position3=right|mark=Cyan pog.svg\n|lat4=4.638596|long4=101.0636|label4_size=65 |label4=[[Jelapang, Perak|Jelapang]]|position4=left|mark4=Cyan pog.svg\n|lat5=4.529513|long5=101.129836|label5_size=65 |label5=[[Simpang Pulai]]|position5=right|mark5=Cyan pog.svg\n|lat6=4.56836|long6=101.050314|label6_size=65 |label6=[[Menglembu]]|position6=left|mark6=Cyan pog.svg\n}}\n\n=== Topography ===\nIpoh is in the state of [[Perak]], which is in the northern part of [[Peninsular Malaysia]]. The city is in the middle of the [[Kinta Valley]], on the bank of the [[Kinta River]] and the confluence of smaller rivers, Sungai Pinji and Sungai Pari. The city is surrounded by limestone hills, which can be found around suburban areas to the northeast, east and southeast.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.malaysiahotelreview.com/perak/destination/limestone-hill.shtml |title=Limestone Hills (Bukit Batu Kapur), Ipoh, PERAK \u2013 Malaysia Travel Review |publisher=Malaysiahotelreview.com |accessdate=10 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe Kledang mountain range stretches from the north to the west of the city. This range runs parallel to the [[Bintang Mountains|Bintang mountain range]] with the [[Perak River]] flowing on its left bank and the [[Kinta River]] to its right. This range is interrupted to the north of Ipoh by a tributary of the [[Perak River]] called the Pelus River, which is sourced from the [[Titiwangsa Mountains|Titiwangsa mountain range]], which runs to the east of Ipoh.<ref>{{cite book |last= Jacq-Hergoualc'h |first= Michel |author2=Victoria Hobson |title= The Malay Peninsula: Crossroads of the Maritime Silk Road (100 BC \u2013 1300 AD) |publisher= [[Brill Publishers|BRILL]] |date=September 2002 |isbn= 90-04-11973-6}}</ref>\n\n=== Climate ===\nIpoh features a [[tropical rainforest climate]] more subject to the [[Intertropical Convergence Zone]] than the [[trade wind]]s and with very rare [[cyclone]]s so an equatorial climate. Temperatures are about the same throughout the year, showing little variation. The city's average temperature is {{Convert|28|C}}. Ipoh sees high precipitation throughout the year with an average of {{Convert|200|mm|abbr=on}} of rain each month and averaging {{Convert|2427.9|mm|abbr=on}} of rain per year. The wettest month is October where on average {{Convert|297.2|mm|abbr=on}} of rain is seen. Ipoh's driest month is January which has {{Convert|132.3|mm|abbr=on}} of rain fall on average.\n\n{{Weather box|width=auto\n| location     = Ipoh\n| metric first = y\n| single line  = y\n| Jan high C = 32.9\n| Feb high C = 33.7\n| Mar high C = 33.9\n| Apr high C = 33.7\n| May high C = 33.5\n| Jun high C = 33.3\n| Jul high C = 33.0\n| Aug high C = 33.0\n| Sep high C = 32.5\n| Oct high C = 32.4\n| Nov high C = 32.1\n| Dec high C = 32.1\n| year high C = 33.0\n| Jan low C = 22.6\n| Feb low C = 23.0\n| Mar low C = 23.4\n| Apr low C = 23.9\n| May low C = 24.0\n| Jun low C = 23.7\n| Jul low C = 23.2\n| Aug low C = 23.3\n| Sep low C = 23.2\n| Oct low C = 23.1\n| Nov low C = 23.1\n| Dec low C = 22.8\n| year low C = 23.3\n| rain colour = green\n| Jan rain mm = 132.3\n| Feb rain mm = 149.8\n| Mar rain mm = 169.9\n| Apr rain mm = 259.1\n| May rain mm = 210.9\n| Jun rain mm = 151.8\n| Jul rain mm = 156.6\n| Aug rain mm = 157.8\n| Sep rain mm = 216.0\n| Oct rain mm = 297.2\n| Nov rain mm = 275.4\n| Dec rain mm = 251.1\n| year rain mm = 2427.9\n| unit rain days = 1.0 mm\n| Jan rain days = 9\n| Feb rain days = 10\n| Mar rain days = 12\n| Apr rain days = 14\n| May rain days = 14\n| Jun rain days = 10\n| Jul rain days = 10\n| Aug rain days = 12\n| Sep rain days = 15\n| Oct rain days = 18\n| Nov rain days = 18\n| Dec rain days = 15\n| year rain days = 157\n| source 1 = [[World Meteorological Organisation]]<ref name= WMO>{{cite web\n| url = http://worldweather.wmo.int/020/c00077.htm\n| title = World Weather Information Service&nbsp;\u2013 Ipoh\n| publisher = World Meteorological Organisation\n| accessdate = 7 May 2014}}</ref>\n| date     = May 2014}}\n\n=== Limestone caves ===\n[[File:Gua Tempurung.jpg|thumb|The Gua Tempurung Limestone Caves|left]]\n\n[[File:SAM POH TONG LOKE 399.jpg|thumb|[[Sam Poh Tong]], one of the many temples in Ipoh]][[File:Gunung Lang.jpg|thumb|Lang Mountains in Ipoh|left]]\n\nLimestone outcrops rise on the outskirts of Ipoh. There are many caves in these outcrops; cave temples are built in some.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cavesofmalaysia.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060706051626/http://www.cavesofmalaysia.com/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=6 July 2006 |title=Home |publisher=Cavesofmalaysia.com |accessdate=10 December 2013 }}</ref> [[Sam Poh Tong]] is a notable one along with Kek Lok Tong (Chinese: \u6975\u6a02\u6d1e; Cavern of Utmost Happiness), which lies on the other side of the same outcrop. It is accessible through the Gunung Rapat housing area. It has a clean, quiet and cool environment. Other cave temples in Ipoh include Ling Sen Tong, Nan Tian Tong, Kwan Yin Tong and Perak Tong.\n\n[[Gua Tempurung]], near Gopeng south of Ipoh, is a show cave open to the public and popular among [[Caving|spelunkers]]. More than {{Convert|3|km|abbr=on}} long, it is one of the longest caves in Peninsular Malaysia. Part of it has been developed with electric lighting and walkways, and there are tours of different lengths and difficulty. A river passage runs about {{Convert|1.6|km|abbr=on}} through the hill. There are five very large chambers and some stalactites and stalagmites.\n\n== Famous for  \" Malay, Chinese, Indian\" Cuisine  ==\n{{Main|Ipoh cuisine}}\nIpoh has a vibrant food scene with a vast proliferation of hawker centres and restaurants. It is well known for dishes such as \"Sar Hor Fun\" ({{zh|c=\u6c99\u6cb3\u7c89}}) a complete one-dish rice noodle meal with prawn, meat, fish, vegetables and a savoury sauce. Other well known dishes from Ipoh include \"Hor Hee\", flat white rice noodles served with fish cakes and/or fish balls, \"Nga Choi Kai\" ({{zh|c=\u82bd\u83dc\u9e21}}), chicken with soy sauce and beansprouts topped with pepper,\"Kai Shi Hor Fun\" ({{zh|c=\u9e21\u4e1d\u6cb3\u7c89}}) rice noodles with Chicken, \"[[Hakka Mee]]\" ({{zh|c=\u5ba2\u5bb6\u9eb5}}), yellow rice noodles served with mince meat (pork) sauce, \"Tau Fu Fa\", soybean pudding, and Ipoh's famous pastry \"[[Heong Peng]]\" ({{zh|c=\u9999\u9905}}), literally translated to \"fragrant biscuit\". The city is well known in Malaysia for its \"[[Ipoh white coffee]]\" where the coffee beans are roasted with palm-oil margarine and the resulting coffee is served with condensed milk. Ipoh is also known for its fresh fruits such as Pomelo, Durian and Seedless Guava. Ipoh also the home of the famous Ipoh Nasi Kandar or Nasi Vanggey. The dish which is very famous among local citizen and most favorite afternoon dish. When it come's to malay cuisine the best part is their place set up like a village home serving amazing home food example: Nasi lemak with fried Country chicken spicy sambal \"Restoran nasi lemak ayam kampung\" use waze to travel this place. Did you know that IPOH ORIGINAL KACANG PUTIH which means IPOH INDIAN SNACKS is now world famous snack and Indians here now exporting their signature snacks to world wide. Little India is big street which is located in ipoh, famous for Indian cuisine like vegetarian : krishna bhagawan, anandha bhagawan  and for non vegetarian : Thirupathy vilas , old town chapthi . Furthermore, to taste the Authentic South Indian & Clay pot rice visit RESTORAN SRI NAVA JOHTHI 1996 which is located in BUNTONG,ipoh. Their dish normally less preventatives and more to a village method and Clay pot rice is their signature menu which mix with real herbs & spices can blow your mind.    \n\nIn recent years Ipoh has seen an increase in international restaurants, bars and gastropubs have become popular with locals and tourists.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ipoh's bars, gastropubs and nightlife |url=http://travel-tourist-information-guide.com/malaysia-ipoh-bars-clubs-night-life-going-out-drinking-entertainment|website=Travel-Tourist-Information-Guide.com|accessdate=2016-10-08}}</ref>\n\n== Economy  ==\nThe early history Ipoh as a settlement was due to its mining industry although it was playing second fiddle to Gopeng, some 19&nbsp;km / 12 miles to the south.\nIpoh was once, one of the richest cities in Malaysia as well as South East Asia back in the days when tin was king. During the 1980s when tin prices collapsed, the economy of Ipoh was hit particularly hard. However, recently the city gain some momentum. By 2017, the city will open the first Movie Animation Theme Park (MAPS), which is the first ever in South East Asia. Tourism is booming in the city, and many shops in old town Ipoh is being transform into chic caf\u00e9. \nThe city of Ipoh also host some big multi national corporations. Kuala Lumpur Kepong (KLK) Berhad, a palm oil company, which is also among the top 15 biggest companies in Malaysia (By revenue) has its headquarters in Ipoh. \nBatu Kawan Berhad (Which is the biggest shareholder of KLK), an investment company also has its headquarters in Malaysia. \nHovid Berhad, a pharmaceutical company, which is also the first Malaysian companies to introduce generic drugs overseas also has its headquarters in Ipoh. Ipoh also is well known for its white coffee. Old Town Berhad, which is a food & beverage public listed company, specializing in white coffee has its headquarters in Ipoh. \nThere are a few other public listed companies in Ipoh such as Perak Transit Berhad, Tasek Cement Berhad, DKLS Industries Berhad, Wellcall Holding Berhad, Rubberex Berhad, Perak Corp, etc. Ipoh also host some foreign multi national companies Malaysian headquarters. Some of the foreign MNC's in Ipoh is, Finisar, Voith, ITL Asia pacific, Sagami Manufacturers, etc.\n\n== Cityscape ==\n[[File:Ipoh_58.jpg|thumb|Ipoh Skyline]]\n[[File:Ipoh, Perak.jpg|thumb|Jalan Laxamana]]\n\n=== The Old Town ===\nThe Old Town is west of the Kinta River. There is a vibrant commercial district with many historical 'shop-houses' centred around Leech Street ({{zh|c=\u70c8\u6cbb\u8857}}; now Jalan Bandar Timah). Other notable features include:\n* [[Ipoh railway station]] in neo-classical/[[Edwardian Baroque architecture|Edwardian Baroque]] style nicknamed the \"Taj Mahal of Ipoh\".\n* Ipoh Town Hall, an [[Edwardian Baroque architecture|Edwardian Baroque]] municipal building located across the road from the Railway Station.\n* Padang Ipoh or Ipoh Field is on Jalan S.P. Seenivasagam. The field is surrounded by historic buildings that feature classic colonial architecture, including the mock-Tudor style Ipoh Club, FMS Bar, HSBC Building and the [[St Michael's Institution]] secondary school.\n* The [[Anglo-Chinese School, Ipoh]], officially named SMK Methodist (ACS), is located along Lahat Road.\n* [[Sekolah Menengah Kebangsaan Anderson]] is the most well-known secondary school with more than 100 years of history, located beside the General Hospital of Ipoh. This school has been producing numerous of figures in the country.\n* [[St. Michael's Institution]], Ipoh, is a public secondary school in Ipoh, Perak, Malaysia. It is situated on Jalan S. P. Seenivasagam, formerly Clayton Road.\n* [[Han Chin Pet Soo (History Museum)|Han Chin Pet Soo]], the Hakka Tin Miner's Club, located on Jalan Bijeh Timah (formerly Treacher Street) has been restored and turned into Malaysia's First Hakka Tin Mining Museum.\n* Muzium Darul Ridzuan is a historical museum of Perak, in a pretty former tin-mining tycoon's mansion on Jalan Kuala Kangsar.\n*Concubine Lane or better known locally as Yi Lai Hong in Cantonese is a narrow and small lane located off Jalan Bandar Timah (Leech Street) in Old Town, Ipoh. It now has different restaurants, souvenir and gift shops and an entirely respectable hotel. To some locals, Concubine Lane is already becoming too busy.\n*Ipoh wall art murals drawn by talented street art artists clearly breathes in new life into Ipoh Old Town city. The murals do relive a sense of nostalgic moments related to Ipoh\u2019s heritage and culture. It is now a tourist attraction.\n[[File:Old Uncle with White Coffee.jpg|thumb|One of the 7 wall art murals drawn by Ernest Zacharevic in Ipoh old town.]]\n*[[Birch Memorial Clock Tower]] is a historical landmark which is located near the Ipoh State Mosque or commonly known as [[Sultan Idris Shah II Mosque]]. The clock tower was built to commemorate [[James W. W. Birch]], the first British Resident in Perak who was killed on 2 November 1875 at Pasir Salak.\n\n=== The New Town ===\n[[File:Tmn d.r.jpg|thumb|D.R. Seenivasagam Park, formerly Coronation Park]]\nThe so-called New Town, to the east of the Kinta River, was developed by [[Yau Tet Shin]] around 1908.<ref name=\"ipohworld762\" /> The New Town houses the [[Perak Medical University]] and [[Ipoh City Hall]] building, among others. There are numerous shops, shopping malls, and hotels.\n\nD. R. Seenivasagam Park (Coronation Park), located in the heart of Ipoh (New Town), is known for its scenery and recreational facilities.{{fact|date=March 2019}} It comprises recreational fields, an artificial lake filled with fish, a nursery for potted plants and a children's traffic playground.  The latest addition is the newly landscaped [[Japanese garden]] featuring a Japanese [[Koi|carp]] pond.\n\n== Sports ==\n\nFor golf, the courses are the Royal Perak Golf Club off Jalan Sultan Azlan Shah (Tiger Lane), the Meru Golf Club in [[Jelapang, Perak|Jelapang]], and Clearwater Sanctuary Golf Club en route to [[Batu Gajah]].\n\nOther sports venues include the Kilat Club in Pasir Pinji, Ipoh Field (Padang Ipoh) in the Old Town, the [[Polo]] Grounds, and the Iskandar Polo Club, in Ampang Baru.\n\nThe [[Sultan Azlan Shah Cup]] is an annual international men's [[field hockey]] tournament held in Ipoh.\n\nIpoh has a fully equipped sports complex known as Kompleks Sukan MBI or ''MBI Sports Complex''.\n\nAmong the facilities located within the Complex is the Stadium Perak or [[Perak Stadium]]. [[Perak Stadium]] is the home of [[Perak FA|Perak The Bos Gaurus]] who playing in [[Malaysia Super League]].\n\n== Governance ==\n[[File:Ipoh City Council.jpg|thumb|[[Ipoh City Council]]]]\n\nThe [[Ipoh City Council]] governs the city. Datuk Zamri Man, appointed in August 2015, is the current mayor of Ipoh.<ref>{{Cite web|title = New mayor for Ipoh sworn in \u2013 Community {{!}} The Star Online|url = http://www.thestar.com.my/Metro/Community/2015/08/10/New-mayor-for-Ipoh-sworn-in/|website = The Star|location=Malaysia|accessdate = 11 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nIpoh is divided into two parliamentary constituencies: ''Ipoh Barat'' (Ipoh West) and ''Ipoh Timur'' (Ipoh East). The parliamentary seat for ''Ipoh Timur'' is held by DAP Representative, Su Keong Siong, which was formerly held by [[Lim Kit Siang]] while the seat for ''Ipoh Barat'' is held by fellow DAP leader, [[M. Kulasegaran]].<ref>[http://temanpetunjuk.blogspot.com/2009/02/analisa-dewan-undangan-negeri-dun-perak.html]{{dead link|date=September 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Demographics ==\nIpoh remains one of [[Malaysia]]'s largest cities. It is the third largest city in Malaysia. As of 2010, the municipal area of Ipoh has a population of 657,892.<ref name=\"census 2010\">{{cite web|title=Population Distribution by Local Authority Areas and Mukims, 2010|url=http://www.statistics.gov.my/portal/download_Population/files/population/04Jadual_PBT_negeri/PBT_Perak.pdf|publisher=Department of Statistics Malaysia |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120227011347/http://www.statistics.gov.my/portal/download_Population/files/population/04Jadual_PBT_negeri/PBT_Perak.pdf |archivedate=27 February 2012 }}</ref> It ranks as the seventh most [[List of urban areas in Malaysia by population|populous urban centre]] in Malaysia (2010).<ref name=\"census 2010\" />\n\nThe following is based on Department of Statistics Malaysia 2010 census.<ref name=\"census 2010\" />\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=3| Ethnic groups in Ipoh, 2010\n|-\n! [[Ethnicity]] !! Population !! Percentage\n|-\n| [[Chinese Malaysian|Chinese]] || 290,165 || 44.11%\n|-\n| [[Bumiputera_(Malaysia)|Bumiputera]] || 253,592 || 38.55%\n|-\n| [[Malaysian Indian|Indian]] ||  92,587 || 14.07%\n|-\n| Others || 1,559 || 0.2%\n|-\n| Non-Malaysian || 19,989 || 3.04%\n|}\n\n=== Toponymy ===\nThe name Ipoh is derived from a local tree, ''Pohon Epu'' or now more commonly known as [[Upas Tree|''Pokok Ipoh'']]. The sap of this plant is poisonous and was used by [[Orang Asli]] ([[indigenous peoples]] in [[Malay language|Malay]]) to coat the tips of the darts of their blowpipes for hunting.\n\n== Transport ==\n[[File:Sultan Azlan Shah Airport.JPG|thumb|[[Sultan Azlan Shah Airport]]]]\n* Trunk roads: The old interstate [[Malaysia Federal Route 1|Route]] {{JKR|1}} connects Ipoh with other major towns and cities in peninsular Malaysia, for example to [[Alor Setar]], [[Taiping, Perak|Taiping]] and [[Penang]] to the north and [[Tapah]], [[Kuala Lumpur]], [[Seremban]] and even [[Johor Bahru]] in the south. Motorists from the east coast can use [[Malaysia Federal Route 4|highway]] {{JKR|4}} (from [[Gerik]]) in northern Perak or {{JKR|185}} (from [[Cameron Highlands]]).\n* Highway: The new [[North\u2013South Expressway (Malaysia)|North\u2013South Expressway]] {{MES-E|1}} is a faster and more efficient alternative to Route 1. However, certain towns like [[Kampar, Perak|Kampar]] can only be accessible via Route 1.\n* Train: [[Ipoh railway station|Ipoh's railway station]] is operated by [[Keretapi Tanah Melayu]] (KTM) and is in the Old Town (however, it does not have intra-city travel like in [[Kuala Lumpur]]). The railway only connects Ipoh with neighbouring towns and cities. The station is a stately building, referred to by locals as the 'Taj Mahal' of Ipoh. [[KTM Intercity]] began the Shuttle Train Service between [[Kuala Lumpur]] and Ipoh from 1 December 2008 while the modern [[Electric Train System]] (ETS) shuttle began from 12 August 2010 with average {{Convert|145|km/h|abbr=on}} speed, plying Ipoh-Seremban route, cut the travelling distance between Ipoh and [[Kuala Lumpur]] into 120&nbsp;minutes. There are 10 dedicated shuttle train services between these two cities daily which begins at 5&nbsp;am from both the stations. Travel time between the cities was expected to be reduced from three hours to two hours and fifteen minutes when the new set of EMU trains arrived in mid-2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cockatoo.com/malaysia/e-06pera/em-per27.htm |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130119155613/http://www.cockatoo.com/malaysia/e-06pera/em-per27.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=19 January 2013 |title=Malaysia / Perak / The Ipoh Railway Station |publisher=Cockatoo.com |date=14 November 2011 |accessdate=10 December 2013 }}</ref>\n* Bus: The inter-city bus terminal is located at [[Amanjaya Integrated Bus Terminal]] in [[Bandar Meru Raya]], just north of the city.\n* Air:  the [[Sultan Azlan Shah Airport]] is the only airport in Ipoh. It is near [[Gunung Rapat]]. Domestic flights and international ones are available. [[Scoot]] and [[AirAsia]] provides daily flights out of Ipoh to [[Singapore]] [[Changi Airport]] while [[Batik Air Malaysia]] provides daily flights to [[Senai International Airport|Johor Bahru]].\nThere are also planned flights to Indonesia, Singapore, Thailand and China with talks of a new airport soon.\n\n==Education==\n{{Main|List of schools in Perak}}\n\nThis is a list of schools in Ipoh, Perak.\n*Sekolah Izzuddin Shah \n*[[Sekolah Tuanku Abdul Rahman]] \n*Sekolah Menengah Kebangsaan Tanjung Rambutan\n*Sekolah Menengah Kebangsaan Seri Puteri\n*Sekolah Jenis Kebangsaan(T)ST.Philomena Convent, Ipoh\n*Sekolah Kebangsaan Dato Panglima'Kinta, Ipoh\n*Sekolah Jenis Kebangsaan (C) Yuk Choy, Ipoh\n*SMJK Yuk Choy, Ipoh\n*Tarcisian Convent School, Ipoh (TCS)\n*Anderson School, Ipoh\n*Anglo-Chinese School, Ipoh\n*[[St. Michael's Institution]], Ipoh\n*SMK Jalan Tasek, Ipoh \n*Methodist Girls Secondary School (MGS), Ipoh\n*Perak Girls Secondary School (PGS), Ipoh\n*[[SMK Main Convent]], Ipoh\n*Wesley Methodist School, Ipoh\n*Ipoh International School (Private)\n*Fairview International School, Ipoh\n*Perak Yuk Choy High School (Private) \n*Poi Lam High School (Private), Ipoh ({{zh|c=\u6021\u4fdd\u57f9\u5357\u72ec\u7acb\u4e2d\u5b66}})\n*Shen Jai High School (Private), Ipoh ({{zh|c=\u6021\u4fdd\u6df1\u658b\u72ec\u7acb\u4e2d\u5b66}})\n*Sekolah Jenis Kebangsaan (TAMIL) Kerajaan, Sungai Pari, Ipoh\n*Sekolah Jenis Kebangsaan (TAMIL) Gunung Rapat, Ipoh\n*Sekolah Jenis Kebangsaan (TAMIL) Perak Sangeetha Sabha, Ipoh\n*SMK Rapat Setia, Ipoh\n*SMK Jalan Pasir Puteh, Ipoh\n*Sekolah Jenis Kebangsaan (C) Poi Lam, Ipoh\n*SMK Seri Keledang, Ipoh\n*SMK Menglembu, Ipoh\n*SMJK Poi Lam, Ipoh\n*Sekolah Jenis Kebangsaan (C) Sam Tet, Ipoh ({{zh|c=\u6021\u4fdd\u4e09\u5fb7\u5c0f\u5b66}})\n*[[SMJK Sam Tet]], Ipoh ({{zh|c=\u6021\u4fdd\u4e09\u5fb7\u4e2d\u5b66}})\n*SMK Dato Ahmad Said\n*Sekolah Jenis Kebangsaan Ave Maria Convent, Ipoh ({{zh|c=\u6021\u4fdd\u5723\u6bcd\u739b\u5229\u4e9a\u5c0f\u5b66}})\n*SMJK Ave Maria Convent, Ipoh ({{zh|c=\u6021\u4fdd\u5723\u6bcd\u739b\u5229\u4e9a\u56fd\u6c11\u578b\u4e2d\u5b66}})\n*Sekolah Jenis Kebangsaan (C) Gunung Rapat, Ipoh\n*Sekolah Jenis Kebangsaan (C) Wan Hwa (1)\n*Sekolah Jenis Kebangsaan (C) Wan Hwa (2)\n*Sekolah Kebangsaan (ACS), Ipoh\n*Sekolah Kebangsaan (P) Methodist, Ipoh\n*Sekolah Kebangsaan Haji Mahmud Chemor, Ipoh\n*Sekolah Kebangsaan Kuala Pari, Ipoh\n*Sekolah Kebangsaan Jalan Pegoh\n*Sekolah Kebangsaan Jelapang\n*Sekolah Kebangsaan Marian Convent,Ipoh\n*Sekolah Kebangsaan Raja Ekram, Ipoh\n*SMK Raja Perempuan, Ipoh (RPS) Royal Princess School \"Cluster School\"\n*SRK Raja Perempuan, Ipoh (RPS) \n*Sekolah Kebangsaan Seri Ampang, Ipoh\n*Sekolah Kebangsaan St. Michael's Institution (1), Ipoh\n*Sekolah Kebangsaan St. Michael's Institution (2), Ipoh\n*Sekolah Jenis Kebangsaan (C) Chung Shan\n\n== Theme Parks ==\nThere are several theme parks in Ipoh, including the Sunway Lost World of Tambun <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sunwaylostworldoftambun.com/|title=Lost World of Tambun Ipoh|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> and Movies Animated Park Studios (MAPS).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mapsperak.com/|title=Movies Animation Park, Ipoh Official Website|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180207000455/http://www.mapsperak.com/|archive-date=7 February 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Notable people ==\nFilm and Television:\n* [[Angie Cheong]]\n* [[Mimi Chu]]\n* [[Iqram Dinzly]]\n* [[Mamat Khalid]]\n* [[Peter Pek]]\n* [[Afdlin Shauki]]\n* [[Patrick Teoh]]\n* [[Michelle Yeoh]]\nMusic:\n* [[Guang Liang|Michael Wong]]\n* [[Jamal Abdillah]]\n* [[Shila Amzah]]\n* [[Ning Baizura]]\n* [[Francissca Peter]]\n* [[:ms:Sophia Liana|Sophia Liana]]\n* Sam Chin Neng of [[Fuying & Sam]]\nSports: (Badminton):\n* [[Koo Kien Keat]]\n* [[Choong Tan Fook]]\n* [[Lee Wan Wah]]\n* [[Cheah Soon Kit]]\n* [[Wong Pei Tty]]\n* [[Wong Mew Choo]]\nSports ([[Association football|Football]]):\n* [[Nazirul Naim]]\n* [[Chan Kok Heng]]\n* [[Muhamad Khalid Jamlus]]\nSports (Others):\n* [[Tony Underwood]] (Rugby)\n* [[Nur Suryani Mohd Taibi]] (Sports shooting)\n* [[Leong Mun Yee]] (Diving)\nBusiness:\n* [[David Ho Sue San]] of [[Hovid Berhad]] & Carotech Berhad,\n* [[Lee Loy Seng]] (founder of Kuala Lumpur Kepong Berhad),\n* Dr. [[Wong Jeh Shyan]] CEO of CommerceNet Singapore Limited,\n* [[Koon Yew Yin]] Founder of [[IJM Corporation Bhd]] and [[Gamuda Berhad]]\nPolitics:\n* [[Yeoh Ghim Seng]]\n* [[Yeoh Eng-kiong|Dr Yeoh Eng Kiong]]\n* [[S. J. V. Chelvanayakam]]\n* [[Ahmad Husni Hanadzlah]]\n* [[D. R. Seenivasagam]]\n* [[Lim Keng Yaik]]\n* [[Lee Lam Thye]]\n* [[Chang Lih Kang]]\n* [[Lee Chuan How]]\nHistorical:\n* [[Yusof bin Ishak]] (president of Singapore)\n* [[Leong Sin Nam]]\n* [[Wu Lien-teh]]\n* [[Foo Choo Choon]]\n* [[Leong Fee]]\n* [[Chung Thye Phin]]\n* [[Eu Tong Sen]]\n\nExperts and Academicians:\n* [[Lam Wei Haur]] (Professor Dr in Science)\n\nOther:\n\n* [[Chan Sek Keong]] (Chief Justice of Singapore)\n* [[Lat (cartoonist)|Lat]] (cartoonist)\n* [[Huen Su Yin]] (cake decorating)\n* [[Tang Siew Mun]] (academic)\n* [[Tang Tuck Kan]] (artist)\n\n== Film and television ==\nMovies filmed in Ipoh include:\n* 1992: ''[[Indochine (film)|Indochine]]''\n* 1999: ''[[Anna and the King]]''\n* 2004: ''Tun Tan Cheng Lock''{{Citation needed|date=February 2008}}\n* 2005: ''[[Sepet]]''\n* 2005: ''[[Gubra]]''\n* 2006: ''After This Our Exile (''Chinese'' \u7236\u5b50)\n* 2006: ''Goodbye Boys''\n* 2006: ''[[Lust, Caution]]'' (Chinese: \u8272\uff0c\u6212)\n* 2015: ''[[Blackhat (film)|Blackhat]]''\n\n==Media==\n===[[List of newspapers in Malaysia|Nationwide/National daily newspaper]]===\n====English====\n*''[[Malay Mail]]''\n*''[[New Straits Times]]''\n*''[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]''\n*''[[The Sun (Malaysia)|The Sun]]''\n====Malay====\n*''[[Berita Harian]]''\n*''[[Harian Metro]]''\n*''[[Sinar Harian]]''\n====Chinese====\n*''[[Nanyang Siang Pau]]'' \u2013 \u5357\u6d0b\u5546\u62a5\n*''[[Sin Chew Daily]]'' \u2013 \u661f\u6d32\u65e5\u62a5\n*''[[China Press]]'' \u2013 \u4e2d\u56fd\u62a5\n\n====Tamil====\n*''[[Makkal Osai]]'' \u2013 {{lang|ta|\u0bae\u0b95\u0bcd\u0b95\u0bb3\u0bcd \u0b93\u0b9a\u0bc8}}\n*''[[Malaysia Nanban]]'' \u2013 {{lang|ta|\u0bae\u0bb2\u0bc7\u0b9a\u0bbf\u0baf\u0bbe \u0ba8\u0ba3\u0bcd\u0baa\u0ba9\u0bcd}}\n===Ipoh [[terrestrial television|terrestrial channels]]===\nIpoh [[Free-to-air|free-to-air stations]] include:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n![[Television station]]\n!Channel (via [[MYTV Broadcasting|myFreeview]])\n!Network\n!Broadcast area\n!Broadcast hour\n|-\n| [[TV1 (Malaysia)|TV1 HD]]\n| 101\n| rowspan=2| [[Radio Televisyen Malaysia|RTM]]\n| rowspan=14| National\n| ro